<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jets Stars Respond To Parcells </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. (AP) -- Coach Bill Parcells vented -- and the New  
York Jets responded. 
</P>
<P>
	One day after being criticized by Parcells for lackluster play  
early in training camp, key members of the Jets' explosive offense 
showcased tremendous plays Saturday in the club's first intrasquad 
scrimmage. 
</P>
<P>
	In limited action, quarterback Vinny Testaverde threw for 145  
yards, including sensational touchdown throws of 19 yards to a 
diving Wayne Chrebet and 31 yards to Keyshawn Johnson, who fought 
off a physical defense to snare the pass with only his left hand. 
</P>
<P>
	Those three players had been part of Parcells' harsh attention  
on Friday, when he wondered aloud when the headliners on his 
``Superstar Central'' offense were going to make an impact. 
Testaverde finished 8-for-16 passing, with no interceptions, with 
Johnson catching three passes for 100 yards and Chrebet two for 33. 
</P>
<P>
	``Things like that don't bother me,'' Johnson said of Parcells'  
criticism. ``It goes in one ear and out the other, that superstar 
stuff. He couldn't have been talking about me. I just come in and 
try to help the team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kicker John Hall, who missed a 53-yard field goal attempt,  
connected from 23, 22 and 48 yards. Second-year player Brian Musso, 
fighting for the fourth receiver spot, had four catches for 69 
yards. On defense, linebackers J.J. Syvrud, Olrick Johnson and 
Bryan Cox, along with defensive end Anthony Pleasant, registered 
sacks and safety Victor Green an interception. 
</P>
<P>
	The 90-minute scrimmage, held before approximately 1,000 fans,  
included 91 plays and featured most of the 80-man roster. Included 
in the action was wide receiver Dwight Stone, signed by the team 
late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was some good and some bad,'' Parcells said.  
</P>
<P>
	Parcells supervised the scrimmage only hours before his former  
star linebacker, Lawrence Taylor, was inducted into the Pro 
Football Hall of Fame at Canton, Ohio. The coach, who was not asked 
to introduce Taylor, elected not to attend the ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully, I can see it,'' said Parcells, who expressed  
irritation over some commentaries criticizing his decision to stay 
away from Canton. ``I'm very proud of him. I heard someone on the 
radio today refer to Parcells' ego and how because he didn't get to 
induct (Taylor) that he didn't go. There could be nothing further 
from the truth.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
