<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jones Ties Season's Best in 100M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Marion Jones tied her fastest time of the year and  
world record holder Maurice Greene cruised to victory on Saturday 
at Crystal Palace in a tune-up for this month's World Championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene's 9.97 seconds at the British Grand Prix was well short  
of the 9.79 he ran in Athens two months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a bit tired now because I have done a lot of racing  
recently,'' Greene said. ``I didn't feel any pressure here today 
and I just had to come out and have fun. 
</P>
<P>
	``But the time proves I am in great shape and I am ready for  
Seville,'' said Greene after he finished clear of Canada's Bruny 
Surin (10.02) and Britain's Dwain Chambers (10.04) with Olympic 
champion Donovan Bailey, still on his way back from long-term 
injury, last in a season's best 10.36. 
</P>
<P>
	The consolation for Greene was that he became the first sprinter  
to run inside 10 seconds on a British track. Not even Linford 
Christie, Britain's former Olympic champion currently at the center 
of drugs allegations, achieved that. 
</P>
<P>
	The American returned to anchor a 4x100 relay team to victory in  
38.02 seconds. The other three runners were Jon Drummond, Ato 
Boldon and Curtis Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	In the women's 100, Jones matched 10.80 she clocked last month  
at Lausanne.	   She finished almost three meters clear of world 200-meter 
champion Zhanna Pintusevich of Ukraine, who clocked 10.98 with 
another American, Inger Miller, third in 11.13. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am so far ahead of the rest of the world that everyone is  
just judging me by my times,'' said Jones, the only runner other 
than the late Florence Griffith Joyner to run inside 10.73. 
</P>
<P>
	Morocco's Hicham El Guerrouj failed in his bid to break the  
world mile record he set a month ago in Rome and Haile Gebrselassie 
was just over three seconds outside the world two-mile mark. 
</P>
<P>
	El Guerrouj eclipsed former world record holders Sebastian Coe,  
Steve Ovett and Steve Cram in running the fastest mile on a British 
track, 3:47.10. Kenya's Laban Rotich finished a distant second in 
3:50.79. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am happy with the time bearing in mind the (hemarroids)  
problems I had,'' said El Guerrouj, who had suffered the illness 
since his world record run. 
</P>
<P>
	Gebrselassie, who has set 15 world records, was left to run the  
last mile of the two-mile race on his own after the pacemakers 
dropped out with the rest of the field at least 50 meters behind. 
</P>
<P>
	With no one to attack him, the Ethiopian made a big late attempt  
to break the record of 7:58.61 owned by his great rival Daniel 
Komen of Kenya but he crossed the line in 8:01.72 with no one else 
within 100 meters. 
</P>
<P>
	Kenyans finished second and third, Paul Bitok clocking 8:16.44  
and James Kosgei 8:16.78. 
</P>
<P>
	Morocco's Zahra Ouaziz ran the fastest women's 5,000 meters in  
the world this year with a 14:42.03. 
</P>
<P>
	Christie was expected to be at the meet to coach his sprinters  
but decided not to attend because he was concerned that the 
publicity surrounding his suspension would be a distraction for the 
athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	The 39-year-old 1992 Olympic 100m champion, who is retired but  
runs for fun, was suspended after failing a drugs test at Dortmund 
in February. A test detected the presence of metabolites of the 
banned steroid nandrolone and news reports on Saturday said the 
levels were 100 times the permitted amount. 
</P>
<P>
	Christie has declared his innocence saying the tests were flawed  
and UK Athletics, which is responsible for the sport in Britain, 
has launched a campaign for more accurate tests for nandrolone. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
