<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Walden Looking for Menifee Race Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OCEANPORT, N.J. (AP) -- Trainer Elliott Walden can only hope that  
history repeats itself for Menifee in Sunday's $1 million Haskell 
Invitational at Monmouth Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Menifee, who has never raced at the same track twice, will be  
returning to the site where he broke his maiden on July 16, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides returning to the Jersey shore track, Menifee should also  
benefit from having regular jockey Pat Day in the saddle. 
</P>
<P>
	Day had his choice of riding either favored Menifee, who was  
second in the Kentucky Derby and Preakness, or 2-1 second choice 
Cat Thief. 
</P>
<P>
	It probably wasn't a hard decision for Day. The two 3-year-olds  
have gone head-to-head four times and Menifee has come out ahead 
each time. 
</P>
<P>
	``My horse beat Cat Thief three times this year,'' Walden said.  
``I don't know if he'll beat him again on Sunday or not but I think 
that advantage was part of Pat's decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Pat has ridden Menifee in all but his first start and he has a  
lot of faith in him, as do I.'' said Walden. ``I think he made the 
right decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The only question with Menifee seems to be whether he can  
rebound from a disappointing eighth-place finish in the Belmont 
Stakes on June 5. Prior to that, he had run either first or second 
in every race he had entered. He has not raced since then. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know why he ran so poorly,'' Walden said. ``It was  
uncharacteristic. Maybe he had a virus, maybe he was just at the 
end of a long road. He's been off for a while and he seems good 
now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Menifee's chief competition should come from Cat Thief, who is  
trained by D. Wayne Lukas and will be ridden by Mike Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	Cat Thief won the Swaps Stakes at Hollywood Park on July 18 with  
Day in the saddle after finishing third in the Kentucky Derby and 
seventh in the Preakness. He did not enter the Belmont. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, who is two-for-two in the Haskell, is hoping for a replay  
of last year's race when his horse Coronado's Quest took the lead 
and held on to beat Walden's Victory Gallop down the stretch. 
</P>
<P>
	``Monmouth has always been a speed favoring track and I think  
that suits Cat Thief,'' said Smith. ``You can use the speed to your 
advantage. That's what I did with Coronado's Quest. I opened up 
enough around the far turn so that Victory Gallop couldn't come and 
get us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If either of the favorites, who have drawn the seventh and  
eighth post positions, falter Bob Baffert's Forestry could step up 
with Jerry Bailey on board. The 4-1 third choice has won six of 
eight starts, including the last five in a row. His latest success 
coming in the Grade 2 Dwyer Stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he'll be better than he was in the Dwyer,'' Baffert  
said. ``He didn't go through the Triple Crown so he's a fresh horse 
and that may be the advantage we need.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The other horses in the Haskell field include Woodcarver, Prime  
Directive, Ghost Story, Unbridled Jet and Ecton Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Ecton Park has also been entered in Sunday's Grade 2 Jim Dandy  
Stakes at Saratoga and it Walden may run him there. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
