<DOCNO> APW19990807.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 19:21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Thomas Hits Career Homer No. 300 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- White Sox slugger Frank Thomas hit a solo  
homer into the left-field seats off Oakland starter Kevin Appier 
with one out in the sixth inning for his 300th career home run. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas becomes the 84th player in major league baseball history  
to record 300 home runs. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas also becomes the fifth active player to record at least  
300 homers, 1,000 RBI (1,031) and 1,000 walks (1,050). He joins San 
Francisco's Barry Bonds, Tampa Bay's Fred McGriff, St. Louis' Mark 
McGwire and Baltimore's Cal Ripken, Jr. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas has three career home runs and is batting .360  
(18-for-50) lifetime against Appier. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990807.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 13:10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Official: Russia Must Wean Off Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia needs to wean itself from foreign aid that  
it has been ``eating through'' without achieving long-term 
structural gain, the country's top envoy to international lenders 
said in an interview published Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Mikhail Zadornov also warned that foreign investors will not  
return to Russia until after elections. 
</P>
<P>
	Zadornov's comments in the business daily Kommersant contrasted  
with the optimism among many officials -- including President Boris 
Yeltsin -- after two recent deals with foreign lenders. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Monetary Fund resumed aid to Russia last  
month, disbursing part of a $4.5 billion loan that is the first 
substantial credit for the country since a financial crisis hit a 
year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Then Russia convinced the Paris Club of creditors to reschedule  
$8 billion in Soviet-era foreign debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the agreements come nowhere near the comprehensive  
rescheduling that Russia is seeking for its $150 billion foreign 
debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Zadornov, a former finance minister, acknowledged that the deals  
would provide welcome temporary relief, but said Russia should be 
concentrating on better using foreign aid. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia should ``not just eat through (loans), as we often did in  
recent years,'' he said. ``We should gradually stop the loans from 
the IMF.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also told Kommersant that Russia shouldn't rely on foreign  
investors to boost the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Private investors will not come to us before the elections,''  
Zadornov said. He did not indicate whether he meant December 
parliamentary elections or presidential polls scheduled for next 
summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Many foreign investors have pulled out of Russia or scaled back  
since the government defaulted on some debt and devalued the ruble 
last August, freezing the banking system and pummeling Russia's 
financial markets. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
