<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Aug. 7, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Pledges Poverty Fight  
</P>
<P>
	HELENA, Ark. (AP) -- President Clinton today promised to devote  
the rest of his term to eliminating the poverty that clings to this 
neglected corner of his home state and other parts of the delta 
region, where unemployment is twice the national averageplaces like 
this neglected corner of his home state. Clinton stopped in Helena 
for a private meeting with 54 local officials, who are organizing a 
commission to take on the enormous problems of the Mississippi 
Delta, from education to housing and civic infrastructure. The 
president submitted his so-called ``new markets'' legislative 
proposal to Congress last week. It includes a series of tax 
incentives and lending guarantees for new investment. 

</P>
<P>
	Black Gets S. African Bank Post  
</P>
<P>
	JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- A black man assumed control of  
South Africa's all-important central bank today, moving forward the 
country's transformation from a white-dominated land to a 
multiracial society. Tito Mboweni, a former labor minister, becomes 
Reserve Bank governor while most of South Africa's majority blacks 
remain mired in poverty five years after apartheid collapsed. 
Mboweni shoved aside notions that the Reserve Bank should 
accelerate the transformation of South Africa from a society where 
only whites had privilege to one where opportunity awaited 
everyone, saying: ``Our role is to ensure there is a stable 
financial environment. Our mandate is very narrow.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Governors Warn Congress on Tax Plan  
</P>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Republican governors applauded the  
congressional tax cut plan today but warned that they will not let 
GOP lawmakers raid state budgets to pay for it. Several governors 
accused fellow Republicans in Washington of trying to renege on 
pledges to ship the money to states. They suggested the development 
could damage their promised partnership with Washington. Republican 
congressional leaders have considered asking the nation's governors 
to return up to $6 billion in welfare money to help balance the 
books on their 10-year, $792 billion tax cut proposal. 

</P>
<P>
	French Troops Fend Off Albanians  
</P>
<P>
	KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Amid curses, shoving and  
obscene gestures, dozens of French troops today fought back 
hundreds of ethnic Albanians trying to cross into the Serb section 
of a northern Kosovo town. As this simmering dispute over free 
movement erupted, soldiers kept the ethnic Albanians from crossing 
a bridge over the Ibar River. An equally agitated Serb crowd jeered 
from the far side. Local leaders of the Kosovo Liberation Army, the 
ethnic Albanian guerrilla group being disbanded under an agreement 
with NATO, led the protest and eventually persuaded the crowd to 
disperse after the four people arrested were freed. 

</P>
<P>
	Official: Russia Must Wean Off Aid  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia's top envoy to international lenders said  
the country needs to wean itself from foreign aid because it has 
been ``eating through'' financial assistance without achieving 
long-term structural gain. Mikhail Zadornov, a former finance 
minister, acknowledged that aid from the international community 
would provide welcome temporary relief, but said Russia should 
concentrate on better using foreign aid. Many foreign investors 
have pulled out of Russia or scaled back since the government 
defaulted on some debt and devalued the ruble last August, freezing 
the banking system and pummeling Russia's financial markets. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Says Tax Cuts Hurt Education  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- President Clinton today announced $120  
million in new school grants to make a college education more 
accessible to America's young people, but said ``Operation Gear 
Up'' is threatened by the Republicans' $792 billion tax-cut 
package. ``Now is not the time to turn our backs on our children's 
future,'' the president said in his weekly radio address. 

</P>
<P>
	SMU Faithful Rattled by Allegations  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- As former Mustang Eric Dickerson was inducted into  
the NFL Hall of Fame, those connected with Southern Methodist 
University struggled to digest news of an investigation into 
alleged irregularities involving an SMU defensive line coach. The 
mere whiff of alleged impropriety is enough to rattle SMU faithful 
still recovering from the shame of the 1980s football scandal that 
earned the only NCAA death penalty ever imposed. SMU athletic 
director Jim Copeland announced late Friday that the alleged 
problems surrounding assistant coach Steve Malin, were uncovered 
about 2 1/2 weeks ago during a routine compliance check. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY FOSS  
  	   	
</P>
