<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands Battle Nevada Wildfires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNEMUCCA, Nev. (AP) -- Cooler temperatures and higher humidity  
helped firefighters make progress Saturday in their battle against 
more than 100 fires that had blackened 1 million acres of brush and 
grass. 
</P>
<P>
	However, flames threatened numerous ranch structures in the  
Denio area near the Oregon border and a state transportation 
department maintenance station on I-80 west of Elko. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, two homes were burned near Elko.  
</P>
<P>
	Most of the fires were burning along a 200-mile stretch of  
Interstate 80, northern Nevada's major artery, between Lovelock and 
Elko. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been here for four decades and I've never seen anything  
like this,'' said Bureau of Land Management spokesman Bob Stewart. 
</P>
<P>
	The fires had blackened more than 1,500 square miles, an area  
larger than Rhode Island. 
</P>
<P>
	No estimated containment time for the fires was being offered,  
said firefighters' spokeswoman Judith Dyess. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the fires in remote, uninhabited range had been started  
by lightning. 
</P>
<P>
	Smoke intermittently closed Interstate 80 on Friday near  
Lovelock, Winnemucca, Battle Mountain and Elko. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
