<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Krayzelburg Sets Backstroke Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Lenny Krayzelburg broke his own American  
record in the 200-meter backstroke Saturday in the second day of 
competition of the National Swimming Championships at the 
University of Minnesota Aquatic Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Krayzelburg was on pace to snap the world mark, held by Spain's  
Martin Zubero (1 minute, 56.57 seconds), but the 23-year-old 
resident of Studio City, Calif., finished in 1:56.68 to win his 
ninth national title. 
</P>
<P>
	Defending world champion Jenny Thompson narrowly missed breaking  
her own national record in the 100-meter freestyle. Thompson, of 
Menlo Park, Calif., finished in 54.66, just 0.18 seconds off the 
mark she set in 1992. It was the 21st national title for the 
26-year-old Thompson, who moved into a tie for 11th place on the 
career list of American national titles with Gary Hall and Eleanor 
Holm-Jarrett. 
</P>
<P>
	Four-time 1996 Olympic gold medalist Amy Van Dyken, absent from  
competition since the 1998 Spring Nationals due to shoulder 
surgery, came in second (55.99) despite having to wear a men's body 
suit after breaking two of her own while getting dressed. 
</P>
<P>
	Youth dominated the 200-meter breaststroke, as 14-year-old  
Kristen Caverly (2:30.11) and 17-year-old Brendan Hansen (2:16.07) 
earned national titles. 
</P>
<P>
	Other champions included Jason Lezak in the men's 100-meter  
freestyle (49.34), Lindsay Benko in the women's 200 backstroke 
(2:12.26), Misty Hyman in the women's 200 butterfly (2:10.14) and 
Ugur Taner in the men's 200 butterfly (1:58.82). 
</P>
<P>
	About 1,400 swimmers are competing in the five-day meet, which  
should produce 10 additional qualifiers for the U.S. team in the 
Pan Pacific Games Aug. 22-28 in Sydney, Australia. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
