<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Defected Cuban Coach Looking for Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- The Cuban pitching coach who defected in  
Baltimore two months ago still is waiting for permission to work in 
the United States, his dreams of working for a major league team on 
hold. 
</P>
<P>
	Rigoberto Betancourt Herrera did not return with the Cuban team  
that played an exhibition game in early May against the Orioles in 
Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	Within weeks of slipping out of the Sheraton Inner Harbor Hotel  
and hiding beneath a row of bushes for six hours in downtown 
Baltimore before seeking asylum at a police station, Betancourt 
Herrera said, the Boston Red Sox interviewed him for a job, 
coaching minor leaguers at their training camp in Fort Myers, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	That was more than two months ago. The U.S. Immigration and  
Naturalization Service has granted Betancourt Herrera political 
asylum. But under INS rules, he has to wait until October to apply 
for a work permit. It could take a few more months before 
permission is granted. 
</P>
<P>
	Betancourt Herrera told The (Baltimore) Sun he's worried that a  
job with the Red Sox could be gone by then. 
</P>
<P>
	Kent Qualls, the team's director of player development, said  
nothing is guaranteed until Betancourt Herrera receives INS 
approval. 
</P>
<P>
	``Until he gets his working papers, there's nothing to talk  
about,'' Qualls said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I were working, I'd be the happiest man in the world,''  
Betancourt Herrera, 55, said. ``Now, I'm worried. I don't have any 
doubts about my decision. But I have doubts about working in this 
country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At 5 feet, 6 inches, Betancourt Herrera became known as the  
``Little Giant,'' a pitcher who could ring up as many as 18 
strikeouts a game. He was later selected to the national teams that 
played during the Central American-Caribbean games in Puerto Rico 
in 1966 and the Pan American Games in Winnipeg in 1967. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
