<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Saudis To Boycott Qatar Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DOHA, Qatar (AP) -- Saudi Arabia will boycott a handball  
tournament in Qatar later this month because of the presence of an 
Israeli team, al-Sharq newspaper reported Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Saudi Arabia has officially informed Qatar's Foreign Ministry  
that it will not attend the World Youth Handball Tournament, the 
paper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Saudi officials were not available for comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Saudi Arabia does not recognize the state of Israel, believing  
it is usurped Palestinian land. 
</P>
<P>
	Israel's participation in games has also been condemned by many  
Qataris. The Qatari press lashed out at the government for allowing 
Israel to participate and has urged the public to boycott the 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	Qatar has limited commercial ties with the Jewish state, but no  
diplomatic ties. Most Qataris sympathize with fellow-Arab 
Palestinians, Lebanese and Syrians in their territorial disputes 
with Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	Qatari officials have said the Israelis were welcome and that  
they would secure visas for Israeli fans if requested, in keeping 
with the rules of the International Handball Federation. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-two teams were to participate in the Aug. 22 to Sept. 6  
tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	The other Arab teams that are to take part are Egypt, Tunis,  
Bahrain, Kuwait and host Qatar. 
</P>
<P>
	Qatar has been trying to promote itself as a sports venue and is  
the first Gulf country to regularly host international meets. The 
emirate hopes to win the right to stage the 2006 Asian Games. 
</P>
<P>
 *fsa-sf 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
