<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Aug. 7, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	French Troops Fend Off Albanians  
</P>
<P>
	KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Amid curses, shoving and  
obscene gestures, dozens of French troops today fought back 
hundreds of ethnic Albanians trying to cross into the Serb section 
of a northern Kosovo town. As this simmering dispute over free 
movement erupted, soldiers kept the ethnic Albanians from crossing 
a bridge over the Ibar River. An equally agitated Serb crowd jeered 
from the far side. Local leaders of the Kosovo Liberation Army, the 
ethnic Albanian guerrilla group being disbanded under an agreement 
with NATO, led the protest and eventually persuaded the crowd to 
disperse after the four people arrested were freed. 

</P>
<P>
	Aid Denied for African Kidnappers  
</P>
<P>
	FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Sierra Leone's president today  
urged international groups to provide food and medicine to 
rebel-allied soldiers, but an aid official insisted that donors 
were determined not to help the combatants, who are holding about 
30 hostages. Ahmed Tejan Kabbah told journalists that foreign 
relief organizations should review policies of refusing assistance 
to armed groups ``in this exceptional case.'' The aid official, 
speaking on condition of anonymity, said that providing food to 
combatants would start a dangerous precedent. 

</P>
<P>
	Neo-Nazi March Canceled  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Even though the city closed a number of  
streets and spent an estimated $1 million on police to protect 
them, a neo-Nazi group abruptly canceled its planned rally today in 
the nation's capital. The march was canceled because huge counter 
demonstrations were planned and ``the media worked this thing up 
into a frenzy,'' said Jeff Krause, executive vice president of the 
American Nationalist Party. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Governors Wary of Tax Plan  
</P>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Republican governors applauded Congress' tax  
cut plan today but warned that they will not let GOP lawmakers raid 
state budgets to pay for it. Republican congressional leaders have 
considered asking the nation's governors to return up to $6 billion 
in welfare money to help balance the books on their 10-year, $792 
billion tax cut proposal. Several governors accused fellow 
Republicans in Washington of trying to renege on pledges to ship 
the money to states. Adding to the governors' bitterness is the 
fact that the first word of a plan to seek state money came from 
press accounts -- not their leadership in Washington. 

</P>
<P>
	Official: Russia Must Wean Off Aid  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia needs to wean itself from foreign aid that  
it has been ``eating through'' without achieving long-term 
structural gain, the country's top envoy to international lenders 
said in an interview published today. Mikhail Zadornov also warned 
that foreign investors will not return to Russia until after 
elections. Zadornov's comments in the business daily Kommersant 
contrasted with the optimism among many officials -- including 
President Boris Yeltsin -- after two recent deals with foreign 
lenders. Zadornov, a former finance minister, acknowledged that aid 
from the international community would provide welcome temporary 
relief, but said Russia should concentrate on better using foreign 
aid. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Says Tax Cuts Hurt Education  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- President Clinton today announced $120  
million in new school grants to make a college education more 
accessible to America's young people, but said ``Operation Gear 
Up'' is threatened by the Republicans' $792 billion tax-cut 
package. ``Now is not the time to turn our backs on our children's 
future,'' the president said in his weekly radio address. 

</P>
<P>
	More Rain Forecasted for Asia  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Across Asia, where floods have killed  
more than 950 people and left millions homeless, people were 
struggling to clean up from several weeks of devastating floods 
caused by heavy rains and storms. Low-lying towns north of Seoul, 
the South Korean capital, looked like huge garbage dumps today. 
Streets were clotted with broken furniture that residents had 
rescued from their sodden homes, and crumpled cars lay overturned. 
Weather forecasters said seasonal monsoon rains are likely to 
continue for much of this month in Southeast Asia, raising fears in 
the region's many countries of further flooding. 

</P>
<P>
	Red Sox Beat Angels 14-3  
</P>
<P>
	ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Nomar Garciaparra had three hits and  
Brian Daubach went 3-for-6 with three runs and a solo homer as the 
Boston Red Sox beat the Anaheim Angels 14-3. Pat Rapp (4-5) was the 
recipient of the offensive support. Garciaparra, the AL's leading 
hitter at .364, scored two runs and hit his 28th double of the 
year. Jose Offerman went 3-for-5 with three RBIs. All 10 Boston 
players who batted either scored or drove in a run as the Red Sox 
had 19 hits. Taking advantage of sloppy defense and a rusty Tim 
Belcher (5-7), who had been on the disabled list, Boston jumped out 
to a 7-0 lead in the third inning. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY FOSS  
  	   	
</P>
