<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cubs May Open 2000 in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Chicago Cubs players are willing to open the 2000  
baseball season with a two-game series against the New York Mets in 
Japan if an acceptable agreement can be worked out with the players 
union. 
</P>
<P>
	``There wasn't a vote, but the team has agreed we want to go,''  
player representative Steve Trachsel said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Issues that still need to be decided are flight schedules,  
accommodations, off days and the number of family members allowed 
to go along, Trachsel said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The experience would be great. I think we're the last major  
sport not to play overseas. That would be great to expand the 
sport, and of course Sammy's popularity is a big thing,'' Trachsel 
said, referring to Cubs slugger Sammy Sosa. 
</P>
<P>
	Sosa traveled with Major League Baseball's postseason exhibition  
team last fall and was hailed by Japanese fans. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubs will wait to take an official vote on the offer until  
after negotiations with Japanese officials are over. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
