<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Racer Fernandez Out Indefinitely </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Patrick Racing driver Adrian Fernandez is out  
indefinitely while he recuperates from surgery to repair his broken 
right wrist. 
</P>
<P>
	Fernandez was injured during Friday morning's practice session  
for the Tenneco Automotive Grand Prix of Detroit when he crashed in 
Turn 2. He was flown to Methodist Hospital in Indianapolis late 
Friday and had surgery to insert a plate and screws. 
</P>
<P>
	The injury forced Patrick to withdraw Fernandez' car from  
qualifying. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is obviously a very unfortunate and sad situation,'' team  
owner Pat Patrick said Saturday. ``Adrian was off to a very strong 
start and is a contender for the PPG Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``The most important things are that he receives the best  
medical care possible and that he has a full recovery.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Patrick said Dr. Terry Trammell, CART's chief orthopedic  
consultant, will examine Fernandez to determine the amount of time 
he will be sidelined from the Indy-car circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Fernandez is currently fifth in the FedEx Series championship  
points standings with 95 points. He had finished in the top six in 
the last five races. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *DRIVER SEARCH:* The search is on for another Canadian driver to  
replace Greg Moore, who is leaving the Players Forsythe Racing Team 
at the end of the 1999 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore, along with Gil de Feran, will drive for Penske Racing  
beginning next season. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's with mixed feelings that we will be ending our  
relationship with Greg at the end of this season,'' Mark Thorne, 
marketing communications manager for the Players team, said 
Saturday at a news conference. ``We will now provide another 
Canadian driver with the opportunity to make the jump to CART and 
follow in the footsteps of Jacques Villeneuve, Greg Moore and 
Patrick Carpentier.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thorne would not identify who the new driver will be. He said  
the team is scheduling testing with various drivers. 
</P>
<P>
	Players will continue to sponsor a two-car team next year,  
Thorne said. However, he noted that all of Players' auto racing 
sponsorship will cease in 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are committed to (team owner) Jerry (Forsythe) and to  
Players Forsythe Racing next year at the two-car level,'' said 
Thorne. ``With the Canadian tobacco legislation, currently there 
will be restrictions placed on us in the year 2000 as to the way we 
advertise. Unfortunately in October 2003, we will not be able to 
sponsor many activities and the racing program will come to a 
halt.'' 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SUPER SUB:* Roberto Moreno, also known as ``super sub,'' made a  
super jump in Saturday's final round of qualifying. 
</P>
<P>
	Filling in for the injured Christian Fittipaldi, Moreno sped to  
the fifth-fastest qualifying lap of 114.338 mph. On Friday, he had 
the 19th best speed of 110.501. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm extremely happy,'' Moreno said. ``After Friday, I knew the  
only thing we could do was get better. The car was very good today. 
The team did a wonderful job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fittipaldi was injured Monday when he crashed his Newman-Haas  
car during testing at Gateway International Raceway in Madison, 
Ill. He suffered a subdural hematoma and is out indefinitely. 
</P>
<P>
	Moreno is fresh off subbing for eight races for PacWest's Mark  
Blundell, who had been out 12 weeks with a burst fracture of his 
seventh cervical vertebrae. Sunday's race will be his eighth career 
start as a driver for Newman-Haas. His best finish with the team 
was fifth place in 1997 at Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a good place for me to switch teams and get used to  
the car,'' Moreno said. ``Most of my career has been on street 
courses. We'll still have room for lots of improvement.'' 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MOTORSPORTS WEB SITE:* PPG Industries, Inc., one of the leading  
sponsors in auto racing, has launched ppgmotorsports.com -- an 
Internet site dedicated to CART, NASCAR, the Indy Racing League and 
Indy Lights. 
</P>
<P>
	The site offers news commentary, exclusive interviews, PPG  
merchandise and free screen savers featuring the PPG pace cars. 
</P>
<P>
	``The popularity of the Internet and motor sports is growing at  
an incredible pace,'' said Rich Zahren, PPG vice president of 
automotive products. 
</P>
<P>
	The site will be updated after each CART, NASCAR, IRL and Indy  
Lights event with current points standings and other information. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
