<HEADLINE> Southern Party Holds Inaugural Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FLAT ROCK, N.C. (AP) -- The Southern Party's inaugural rally drew  
150 supporters Saturday, many in Confederate grey, while party 
leaders pledged to work for a separate Southern nation 
</P>
<P>
	Leaders said this time their struggle would be a peaceful one,  
and short-term goals were to win elections. ``We expect the 
struggle for Southern independence to be a long and tedious 
battle,'' said George Kalas of Houston, the party chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	He condemned violent means and likened the party's efforts to  
independence struggles in Quebec, Scotland, Wales and Ireland. 
</P>
<P>
	The rally was held at an inn where Confederate troops lodged  
during the Civil War. The overwhelmingly white crowd sang 
``Dixie.'' One black woman attended the rally. 
</P>
<P>
	Considering themselves the philosophical heirs to the  
Confederate States of America, the Southern Party has registered 
with the Federal Election Commission and in Florida, Georgia, Texas 
and Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	Party leaders are hoping to eventually send enough members to  
Congress to one day form a separate Southern nation. Party vice 
chairman Jerry Baxley said it was time to fulfill Confederate 
President Jefferson Davis' prophecy that ``the South would rise 
again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some critics have said the group presents a narrow view of the  
South that leaves out blacks and other minorities. Party members 
repeatedly denied that they are racist. 
</P>
<P>
	``Southerners are not a race, they are a people,'' said Kalas,  
whose father is a Greek immigrant. ``There's simply no room in the 
Southern Party for people who are racially bigoted against 
others.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
