<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Braves Helped by Odd Foul Play </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The Braves infielders looked like a bunch of  
Little Leaguers when they let an infield pop-up drop between them 
in the ninth inning of Saturday's 15-4 victory over the San 
Francisco Giants. 
</P>
<P>
	But quick thinking by shortstop Ozzie Guillen turned the miscue  
into an unusual foul ball. 
</P>
<P>
	The towering pop by J.T. Snow fell on the pitcher's mound when  
second baseman Bret Boone called off the other infielders, then 
couldn't reach the ball. 
</P>
<P>
	Guillen let it bounce toward the third-base line. As soon as it  
crossed into foul territory, he grabbed the ball -- turning it into 
a mere foul. Snow then flied out to Ryan Klesko in left field. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you play 20 years in baseball, you've seen it all,''  
Guillen said. ``It's funny when the game is 15-4. It wouldn't have 
been if the score was 1-0.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
