<DOCNO> APW19990807.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 02:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Martin Tired of Being No. 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Mark Martin is tired of being No. 2 at the  
Brickyard. 
</P>
<P>
	Runner-up to Jeff Gordon in last year's Brickyard 400, Martin  
qualified behind Gordon for a second-place start in today's Winston 
Cup race at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	He also is second to Dale Jarrett in the season standings, and  
despite winning on Friday, he finished second to Dale Earnhardt -- 
by a single point -- in this year's International Race of Champions 
series. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't think there was a chance in the world to win the IROC  
championship,'' Martin said. ``But once I was in the car, the race 
was on, like always. 
</P>
<P>
	``Actually, we came kind of close. What Dale Earnhardt did was  
unbelievable, winning three of the four races. We didn't score 
enough points to beat him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earnhardt won the IROC championship and a $225,000 prize with 75  
points. Martin finished with 74 points for $100,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``You just go race, do the best you can,'' Martin said.  
``Sometimes it's good enough; sometimes it's not. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anything that is pressure for you just gets to be more and  
more as the season goes on,'' said Martin, who had 12 top-five 
finishes but only one victory in the first 19 Winston Cup starts 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin was the only driver to finish among the top six each of  
the past four Brickyard races at Indianapolis. He started seventh 
last year, worked his way to the front and led one lap midway 
through the race after Jarrett ran out of gas. Martin was in second 
place and preparing for a dash to the checkered flag when the race 
ended under the yellow following a crash by defending champion 
Ricky Rudd with two laps to go. 
</P>
<P>
	He also started second in 1996 and led 19 laps before finishing  
fourth. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a totally different scenario than qualifying, but we've  
had great races here in the past,'' Martin said. ``The Valvoline 
team is really strong now. They're giving me a great car, and 
they're great in the pits. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's more important to drive a fast car than to start up front  
with a mediocre car. We look at the pole as a competition within a 
competition. We try to qualify as best we can and then perform our 
best in the race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The way the season has gone, Martin is lucky he can even drive a  
car. 
</P>
<P>
	Still recovering from multiple fractures from a crash in  
practice at Daytona last month, he's only now starting to feel 
comfortable. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people might call it tough and some people might call it  
dumb,'' he said of driving with the knee, rib and wrist injuries. 
``Getting through Daytona (in 17th place) was unbelievable torture. 
It feels good to drive a car pain-free.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Martin's 178.941 mph qualifying speed on Thursday was second  
only to Gordon's record 179.612. 
</P>
<P>
	Surprising David Green, whose average starting position in 17  
previous races this season was 34th, qualified third at 178.902, 
just ahead of Jarrett's 178.859. 
</P>
<P>
	The top 25 qualifiers were locked in place. Most of the others  
gambled their speeds would hold up, while Ted Musgrave, Steve Park 
and Rick Mast re-qualified at faster speeds to gain spots in the 
lineup. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven others, including two-time pole starter Ernie Irvan, were  
added as provisional starters based on owners' points. The others 
were Bobby Hamilton, Chad Little, Johnny Benson, Kenny Wallace, 
Jimmy Spencer and Kevin Lepage. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those who failed to make the field were Brett Bodine, the  
Brickyard runner-up in 1994, and veterans Dick Trickle, Morgan 
Shepherd, Rich Bickle and Mike Wallace. 
</P>
<P>
	Rusty Wallace, the older brother of Kenny and Mike, qualified  
17th in the 43-car field, hoping to get his 50th career victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``We got our 49th career win back at Bristol in April and have  
been trying hard to get that 50th win ever since,'' Wallace said. 
``Can you imagine how cool that would be to get the 50th victory in 
the Brickyard 400 at Indy? 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be a hell of a way to go down into the history books,  
I can tell you that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rusty Wallace was the 1989 Winston Cup champion and is 10th in  
points this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had a lot of disappointments this year, a lot of things  
happening to us that we couldn't do anything about,'' he said. ``We 
had a super shot at winning the Daytona 500 back in February and 
lost the thing with 10 laps to go (when he got shuffled to the rear 
of the lead draft). 
</P>
<P>
	``Then we had a pretty good car in Charlotte for the 600 (in  
May) before we crashed out. So, what's left is that third and final 
leg at Indy this week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like Martin, Wallace knows what it's like to finish second at  
Indy. He was runner-up to Dale Earnhardt by .37 second -- about two 
car-lengths -- in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's one race that really sticks out in my mind as one of  
the biggest fish that ever got away,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990807.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 12:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Viking Coach Fan of Scrimmage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANKATO, Minn. (AP) -- Minnesota Vikings coach Dennis Green said  
the injuries to his wide receiving corps won't cause him to 
reconsider his annual intrasquad scrimmage. 
</P>
<P>
	Jake Reed and Robert Tate both sustained shoulder separations  
and Matthew Hatchette came out with a high ankle sprain in Friday 
night's intrasquad scrimmage. 
</P>
<P>
	All are expected to be back for the regular season opener Sept.  
12 against Atlanta, but they could miss a good chunk of the 
remainder of training camp, hurting their timing with the 
quarterbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vikings didn't start camp until Monday and their first  
exhibition game is Friday against the New York Giants. 
</P>
<P>
	``You gotta play,'' Green said. ``You're ready to hit this week  
or you're ready to hit next week. The bottom line is injuries occur 
in football. That's just part of the game. We're going to scrimmage 
next week (against the New Orleans Saints in La Crosse, Wis., on 
Monday) and we can't in my opinion wait until we play the Giants to 
start hitting. Then, you'd have more injuries.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Green tried to be an optimist regarding his injured players  
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tate and Reed have separated shoulders, which are not as  
serious as dislocations. So, we're looking anywhere from two, 
three, four weeks. Maybe two weeks, maybe a little bit more,'' 
Green said. ``Tate's had his before, so it probably heals a little 
faster.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hatchette's high ankle sprain means less swelling but also more  
recovery time, however. 
</P>
<P>
	Green said the Vikings would seek free agent help to restock the  
wide receiving corps during camp to protect starters Cris Carter 
and Randy Moss. 
</P>
<P>
	Reed was beset by injuries all last year, but Green said he was  
confident Reed would be healthy for the opener. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he should be, that's six weeks away, five weeks  
away,'' he said. ``So, we think he should be ready before that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for Hatchette, who emerged during Reed's down time last year,  
nobody's sure when he'll be back on the field. 
</P>
<P>
	``High ankle sprains normally take longer than you'd think,''  
Green said. ``So, that one is probably a minimum of two weeks and 
it could be a lot longer that that. Matthew has never had an ankle 
injury before.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
