<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gas Leak Cause of Texas Hotel Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GRAPEVINE, Texas (AP) -- Investigators confirmed Saturday that a  
gas leak was to blame for a blast that ripped through a new hotel, 
seriously burning a man and injuring dozens with broken glass. 
</P>
<P>
	Fire Marshal Dick Ward said natural gas lines that supplied the  
hotel's swimming pool heater caused the Friday evening explosion at 
the Embassy Suites Outdoor World. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas E. Marcer, a subcontractor who was working on the heater  
when the blast occurred, remained in serious condition Saturday at 
Parkland Hospital in Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	Marcer, interviewed by authorities Saturday in his hospital  
room, and another worker apparently didn't know there was gas in 
the line as they worked on it, Ward said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no negligence involved by either one of these  
technicians,'' the fire marshal said. ``They were doing their jobs 
properly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ward said the gas was ignited either by an electrical pump or an  
ignitor system on the pool equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	The explosion blew through an exterior wall and a gift shop only  
three days after the hotel opened. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten people, including six children, were treated for minor  
injuries at nearby hospitals. About two dozen other people were 
treated by paramedics at the scene for cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said the 330-unit hotel, located near Dallas-Fort  
Worth International Airport, might reopen early next week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990807.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 14:20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Retired Temple Coach Litwack Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Retired Temple University basketball coach  
Harry Litwack, whose 21-year reign included the 1969 NIT 
championship, died of a stroke at his home in Huntingdon Valley 
today. He was 91. 
</P>
<P>
	Litwack, a cigar-smoking gentleman known as ``The Chief,'' had  
been battling a spinal disease for three years when he passed away, 
his wife, Estelle, said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	He coached the Owls from 1952 until his retirement in 1973.  
Litwack's reign included an 89-75 victory over Boston College for 
the 1969 NIT title, and he was inducted into the Basketball Hall of 
Fame in 1975. 
</P>
<P>
	Litwack also led the Owls to the NCAA Final Four in 1956 and  
1958, where the team finished third both times. 
</P>
<P>
	Litwack's 373-193 record also made him the second-winningest  
coach in Temple University, after being surpassed by current head 
coach John Chaney in February. 
</P>
<P>
	Litwack played at Temple in the late 1920s, where he captained  
the team twice in his three years on the varsity. Litwack was 
freshman team coach and assistant varsity coach for 20 years before 
taking over the Temple program in 1952. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basketball really was his life; he loved it,'' Mrs. Litwack  
said. ``He went right from high school on scholarship to Temple and 
stayed there until he retired.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During his years as coach, Litwack soon became known ``The  
Chief'' because of the friendly manner in which he greeted people, 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``When he used to drive a car, if he needed directions and saw a  
pedestrian walking by, he would say, 'Say, chief,''' she said. ``It 
was an expression he said so often when he needed information that 
people soon began calling him that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The name captured the polite gentleman that was Harry Litwack,  
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides his wife, Litwack is survived by two daughters, Lois  
Kieserman and Shelley Smoger, three grandsons and two great 
grandchildren. 
</P>
<P>
	Funeral services are set for 1 p.m. Monday at Goldensteins'  
Rosenberg's Raphael-Sacks in Southampton. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990807.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 16:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marlins Considering Ballpark Sites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The Florida Marlins launched their campaign for a  
new ballpark Saturday by announcing six sites under consideration, 
and owner John Henry said he'll pay for the entire project himself 
if necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	Henry said the location chosen later this year will depend on  
which community most strongly supports a new stadium, which would 
cost an estimated $400 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Henry repeated an earlier pledge that he'll build a ballpark  
even if no tax money is forthcoming. But the expense of financing 
the project entirely with private money would mean a small player 
payroll for years to come and prevent the last-place Marlins from 
becoming competitive, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think that's what this community wants,'' Henry said.  
``It's up to the community to decide how much their share should 
be, rather than me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The plan is for a baseball-only stadium with a retractable roof  
that would open in April 2003. The Marlins will consider four sites 
in Broward County and two in downtown Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	The Broward sites are near Fort Lauderdale City Hall and in the  
suburbs of Lauderhill, Miramar and Davie. The Miami sites are near 
the Miami River and alongside Biscayne Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	In their current home at Pro Player Stadium, the Marlins project  
they'll lose $2.5 million this year despite a player payroll of 
just $19 million. Florida has the worst record in the major leagues 
and ranks ahead of only Montreal in National League attendance, 
averaging 18,144 fans per game. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's about fielding a team which will represent the community  
competitively,'' Henry said. ``We are not a small market. The only 
thing which separates us from the kind of success Cleveland, 
Baltimore, Denver, Atlanta and Dallas have is a ballpark, not 
market size. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today these teams can afford salaries in excess of $60  
million. We cannot. At Pro Player Stadium we cannot afford a $20 
million payroll. A new home will enable the team to have payrolls 
comparable to the most successful franchises in baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Marlins said they're not ready to disclose how they would  
prefer to finance a new ballpark, but Henry said that with similar 
projects elsewhere, public money contributed an average of 80 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The multimillionaire commodities trader bought the team in  
January from founding owner Wayne Huizenga. He reiterated that he 
won't move the Marlins out of South Florida regardless of the 
public response to his appeal for support. 
</P>
<P>
	``Funding will require creativity and commitment, but I'm  
convinced we'll succeed,'' Henry said. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials in both counties say they want any tax increase to be  
approved by voters, which could be difficult. A proposed 1-cent 
sales tax increase for transportation in Miami-Dade was defeated by 
a 2-1 margin last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Marlins officials believe there may be more willingness in  
Broward to help finance a ballpark. Miami-Dade Mayor Alex Penelas 
is opposed to using public money to build stadiums. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990807.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 14:30:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SMU Faithful Rattled by Allegations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- An investigation into possible minor NCAA rules  
violations would register barely a ripple at most schools. Not so 
at Southern Methodist University. 
</P>
<P>
	The mere whiff of alleged impropriety is enough to rattle SMU  
faithful still recovering from the shame of the 1980s football 
scandal that earned the only NCAA death penalty ever imposed. 
</P>
<P>
	And so on Saturday -- the same day former Mustang Eric Dickerson  
was inducted into the NFL Hall of Fame -- those connected with the 
school struggled to digest news of an investigation into alleged 
irregularities involving an SMU defensive line coach. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is an absolute shock,'' said Robert Folsom, an SMU booster  
and co-captain of the late 1940s Mustangs teams that included 
football greats Doak Walker and Kyle Rote. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had been just absolutely annihilated, and we're coming out  
of the absolute pits and it's so hard to believe someone would do 
something like that knowing the problems we've had getting this 
program back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	SMU athletic director Jim Copeland announced late Friday that  
the alleged problems, which date back three or four years, were 
uncovered about 2 1/2 weeks ago during a routine compliance check. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant coach Steve Malin was suspended with pay, and the NCAA  
was notified this past week. Malin couldn't be reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now they're just suspected violations and allegations,''  
Copeland said. ``But there was enough there to merit some type of 
suspension.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A statement from SMU described the issue as ``narrow in scope''  
and ``with no evidence of booster involvement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Narrow or wide, the alleged wrongdoing had to make those who  
suffered through the late 1980s at SMU cringe. 
</P>
<P>
	It was only a dozen years ago that SMU, then an elite college  
program, was hit with the NCAA's harshest punishment after it was 
discovered that a banned booster paid 13 players thousands of 
dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	The pay-for-play scandal included a six-figure slush fund and  
involved Bill Clements, the once and future governor of Texas and a 
former chairman of the SMU Board of Governors. 
</P>
<P>
	SMU's reputation was tarred and the team was killed for two  
seasons. The Mustangs were reborn on Sept. 3, 1989 -- a decade ago 
next month -- as a 98-pound weakling that got clobbered in its first 
game by a lowly Rice team that had lost 18 consecutive games. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't until 1997, under first-year coach Mike Cavan, that  
the Mustangs had another winning season, going 6-5. 
</P>
<P>
	Cavan did not return a call from The Associated Press on  
Saturday. He told The Dallas Morning News that the investigation 
will not affect preparation for the upcoming season. Freshman 
players report for practice starting Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's something that we're going to go through,'' Cavan said.  
``I'm just anxious for us to get in and get started, put this 
behind us and go on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	SMU trustee Cary Maguire on Saturday refused to discuss  
specifics of the Malin case, but said the school has ``zero 
tolerance for NCAA violations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I understood it to be just a very minor infraction and nothing  
to compare with the prior problems that the university had,'' 
Maguire said. ``The university has made a pretty strong effort to 
make people aware of the rules and the desire to comply with 
them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lonnie Kliever, a religious studies professor who led an  
internal investigation of the football program in the 1980s, also 
said it didn't appear the latest alleged problem was a major 
breach. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's always the temptation to cut corners in  
intercollegiate athletics,'' Kliever said. ``I suppose, human 
nature being what it is, even SMU's past couldn't stop this from 
happening again. 
</P>
<P>
	``I take some comfort in the fact that this seems to be an  
isolated incident in that it concerns one coach.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Kliever acknowledged, the incident can't help a  
reputation that was still healing. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the tag we're going to have to live with for a long,  
long time,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
