<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 09:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teen Leads U.S. Swimming Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- There's no question that Kaitlin  
Sandeno is a leader, even at the tender age of 16. 
</P>
<P>
	She's been the president of her freshman and sophomore classes  
at El Toro (Calif.) High School and will be the president of her 
junior class in the fall. 
</P>
<P>
	She's also been the leader of the U.S. swim team at the Pan  
American Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the swimmers have been sinking faster than a lead  
balloon at these games, the precocious Sandeno, a former standout 
soccer player, has stayed afloat. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was an awesome feeling,'' she said Friday night, after  
becoming the first U.S. swimmer to win two individual gold medals 
this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Also grabbing gold Friday was Gerald Tucker, 20, of Cincinnati,  
who easily won the bantamweight title, outpointing Neouar Cermeno 
of Venezuela 15-3. 
</P>
<P>
	``No doubt this is my biggest win ever,'' he said. ``I'll never  
forget this, not for the rest of my life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubans won the other five bouts, with middleweight Arthur  
Palac of Hamtramck, Mich., losing to Yohason Martinez in the 
middleweight division. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. men's basketball team moved into the final against  
Brazil by defeating Argentina 84-76. Brazil took Puerto Rico 95-85. 
</P>
<P>
	Travis Williams scored 19 points to lead the Americans, who will  
try to give the United States it first Pan Ams championship since 
1983. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is why you come,'' U.S. coach Mo McHone said. ``I think  
our guys are focused, we've had great practices and we've really 
had a great effort. I feel like we're where we want to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So was Lea Foreman, of Denmark, Wis., who lifted 474 pounds to  
take the 152-pound class. It was the third U.S. gold in the games 
for a woman weightlifter; Robin Byrd Goad earlier won the 117-pound 
class. Tara Nott won in 105.6 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	The American men won bronze in soccer by beating Canada 2-1.  
Carlos Bocanegra drove in a header off a cross from Cory Gibbs in 
the seventh minute. Then 17-year-old forward Landon Donovan of 
Bayer Leverkusen in Germany added a second off a rebound in the 
60th minute. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicknamed the ``Energizer,'' Sandeno provided a spark for the  
floundering Americans, leading all the way en route to winning the 
women's 800-meter freestyle with a Pan Ams record of 8 minutes, 
34.65 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was something I didn't expect,'' Sandeno said of her  
victories in the 400 and 800 freestyles in her first major 
international competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Sandeno won't have any time to savor her success. Today, she  
left for the U.S. Swimming Championships at Minneapolis. A 
versatile swimmer -- she was the 400 individual medley champion at 
this year's spring nationals -- Sandeno still is undecided in which 
events she will compete at nationals. 
</P>
<P>
	The women's 400 medley relay of Denali Knapp, Staciana Stitts,  
Karen Campbell and Tammie Spatz gave the Americans another gold, 
winning with a games record 4:06.08. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite those victories, the U.S. team has won only seven of 26  
events, its worst showing ever at the Pan Ams. 
</P>
<P>
	Americans led the way today in four of the five preliminaries  
for tonight's finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Spatz, coming back off her strong leg in the winning relay, went  
25.67 in the 50 freestyle, with teammate Shannon Hosack fourth at 
26.22. Beth Botsford, the 1996 Olympic gold medalist in the women's 
100 backstroke, had the fastest qualifying time in the 200 
backstroke prelims, with 2:15.15. 
</P>
<P>
	Joseph Montague was more than two seconds faster than anyone  
else in the prelims of the men's 200 individual medley, clocking a 
career-best 2:02.99, and the men's 400 medley relay team of Justin 
Ewers, Jarrod Marrs, Adam Messner and Dan Phillips led the way into 
the final with a qualifying time of 3:45.34. 
</P>
<P>
	Two others swimmers joined Sandeno as double individual gold  
medalists Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Canada's Joanne Malar earned her 15th Pan Ams medal in three  
Games, winning the women's 200 individual medley in 2:14.18, 
breaking the meet record of 2:14.81 she set in the preliminaries. 
Earlier, she won the 400 IM. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil's Fernando Scherer, the men's 100 freestyle champion, won  
the 50 freestyle at 22.24, after setting the games record of 22.22 
in the prelims. The victory gave Brazil a sweep of all four men's 
freestyle titles. 
</P>
<P>
	The other swimming winners were Canada's Shamek Pietucha in the  
men's 200 butterfly at 1:59.10 and Cuba's Rodolfo Cabrera in the 
men's backstroke at 54.93. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
