<DOCNO> APW19990807.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 02:00:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Piatkowski Signs With Clippers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	For Eric Piatkowski, life with the Clippers for $3 million per  
year was better than the alternative. 
</P>
<P>
	The five-year veteran took the most lucrative deal he could find  
Friday and stemmed the tide of players abandoning the Clippers, 
becoming the first of Los Angeles' many free agents to re-sign with 
the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``You look around the league, everyone can see there's no money  
out there,' he said. ``This is the best deal. I thought about it a 
lot, it was a hard decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Only three free agents signed deals Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	John Wallace, who entered the NBA with the Knicks in 1996 before  
being traded to Toronto, rejoined New York for three years and $6.6 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Jaren Jackson, a key component in the Spurs' push to the NBA  
title last season, decided to stay in San Antonio for a three-year 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first five days of the NBA's trading and signing period,  
the Clippers lost Rodney Rogers and Darrick Martin on the open 
market and worked out a sign-and-trade deal sending Lamond Murray 
to Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	Los Angeles also could lose Lorenzen Wright, who is reportedly  
close to signing a one-year, $2 million contract with the Lakers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no idea what he's going to do,'' Clippers vice  
president Elgin Baylor said. ``I know we're still talking with him, 
it's not a dead issue as far as we're concerned. We would like to 
keep him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sherman Douglas and Tyrone Nesby are the Clippers' other two  
free agents. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps the best remaining unsigned free agent is Mitch  
Richmond, who is holding out hope he can somehow be traded to 
Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	With Seattle, Golden State and Sacramento out of the Richmond  
sweepstakes, Miami was believed to be the only team still trying to 
make a sign-and-trade deal with Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem, however, was that a third team -- Toronto, Chicago  
or the Los Angeles Clippers -- was needed to facilitate a Richmond 
trade under the NBA's salary cap rules. And with the Heat unwilling 
to part with P.J. Brown, it was looking less likely that Richmond 
would be moving on to Miami, his destination of choice. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still give it some hope, but all these deals are very hard  
to do,'' Richmond's agent, Mike Sharpe, said. ``It's a tough 
situation, but we haven't stopped trying.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wright, meanwhile, left everyone wondering why he might sign  
with the Lakers for $2 million when his old team, the Clippers, had 
offered him $30 million for six years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Five million (per season) was put on the table,'' Baylor, the  
Clippers vice president of basketball operations, told the Long 
Beach Press-Telegram. ``He (agent Robert Fayne) didn't find that 
acceptable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fayne and Wright were reportedly meeting with Lakers executives  
Friday, although the team refused to confirm it. 
</P>
<P>
	The news that Wright might sign with the Lakers came as somewhat  
of a shock to Indiana, Minnesota and Atlanta, all of which had 
tried to obtain the forward-center in a sign-and-trade deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The Press-Telegram said the Pacers offered Travis Best and  
Austin Croshere, while the Timberwolves offered Anthony Peeler and 
Dean Garrett. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hawks, who backed off a proposed Jim Jackson-Wright trade  
earlier this week, were believed to have discussed a different 
offer with the Clippers in recent days. 
</P>
<P>
	Fayne did not return numerous phone messages.  
</P>
<P>
	Richmond, offered $30 million over three seasons by the Wizards,  
would accept less money if it would get him traded to the Heat, his 
agent said. 
</P>
<P>
	Golden State had been interested in Richmond, but the Warriors  
could only pay him less than half of what Washington has offered. 
</P>
<P>
	Seattle also tried to get Richmond and would have paid him more  
than Golden State could, but Wizards general manager Wes Unseld 
turned down the Sonics' sign-and-trade proposals. 
</P>
<P>
	``The economic package has to be weighed against everything  
else, and Mitch has said that if he can't get the right economic 
package he wants to go someplace where the team will be 
competitive,'' Sharpe said. ``We haven't given up yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wallace, who had been included in recent three-way trade talks  
involving Miami, Washington and Toronto, decided to sign with the 
Knicks under the middle-class exception. He spent his first NBA 
season with the Knicks and was a fan favorite before being traded 
to Toronto in the Chris Dudley deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we traded John, it was a necessary evil,'' coach Jeff Van  
Gundy said. ``The only way we could get Dudley was to part with a 
quality player, so we made that trade.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson averaged 6.4 points and 2.1 rebounds during the Spurs'  
NBA championship season, the best year of his nine-year career. 
</P>
<P>
	He had several key moments during the Spurs' playoff run. He led  
the team in 3-pointers (31 in 17 games), and averaged 8.2 points 
per game in the postseason. 
</P>
<P>
	Piatkowski, 28, averaged 10.5 points and 2.9 rebounds last  
season, becoming the Clippers' all-time leader in 3-point shots 
attempted and made. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990807.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 18:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't 'Print and Delete' Policy OKd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal agencies may purge records from  
computers once copies of the original documents are made, an 
appellate court has ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision Friday was the first major setback for the advocacy  
group Public Citizen in a records-preservation battle that began a 
decade ago with an effort to keep the White House from destroying 
records of the Iran-Contra affair. 
</P>
<P>
	A three-judge panel of the U.S. Court of Appeals for the  
District of Columbia Circuit overturned a lower court's ban on 
destruction of records. 
</P>
<P>
	Public Citizen sued John Carlin, archivist of the United States,  
and executive branch agencies in 1996 over Carlin's ruling the year 
before authorizing federal agencies to ``print and delete'' from 
government computers electronic mail or word processing records. 
</P>
<P>
	Carlin's position makes such orders applicable to all federal  
agencies. His order allowed paper, microfilm or electronic 
retrieval copying. 
</P>
<P>
	Public Citizen, with the American Library Association, the  
American Historical Association, the Organization of American 
Historians and other research groups, sued on grounds Carlin's 
order violated the U.S. Records Disposal Act and was ``arbitrary 
and capricious.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The court, in a decision written by Judge Douglas Ginsburg,  
ruled that the order did not violate the act, which gave Carlin 
wide discretion to set standards and methods for destroying 
documents. Judges Laurence Silberman and Stephen Williams joined in 
the opinion. 
</P>
<P>
	Essentially, the court said, the plaintiffs did not question  
Carlin's right to order destruction of reproduced original computer 
records but argued that Carlin erred in not requiring electronic 
storage. Such retrieval systems are much easier for researchers and 
others to use than other forms of storage. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our focus, therefore, is upon whether the archivist acted  
arbitrarily and capriciously in determining that a paper copy in a 
paper record-keeping system is an adequate substitute for the 
electronic original,'' the judges wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	They ruled that, although Carlin wrote in issuing his order of  
the benefits of electronic over paper record-keeping, his failure 
to order it was neither arbitrary nor capricious. 
</P>
<P>
	They quoted Carlin's reasoning in a document that accompanied  
the original order: 
</P>
<P>
	``Electronic record-keeping systems may be the best means to  
preserve the content, structure and context of electronic records. 
In addition, an automated system may be more easily searched and 
manipulated than paper records,'' Carlin wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	But, he wrote, ``agencies must create and maintain records to  
conduct government business and account for their activities. Only 
the agency can determine what format best serves these purposes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Public Citizen first challenged the routine destruction of  
electronic records in 1989. A court ordered the government not to 
push ahead with destruction of Iran-Contra e-mail and word 
processing files from the computers of Oliver North and other 
National Security Council officials. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the NSC's ``print and destroy'' policy that Carlin's 1995  
order sent throughout the government. 
</P>
<P>
	The appellate panel's ruling overturned a decision two years ago  
by U.S. District Judge Paul L. Friedman in which he voided Carlin's 
order and instructed him to come up with a permanent plan for 
handling electronic documents by last September. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Friedman's ruling, agencies have backed away from ``print  
and destroy,'' Michael Tankersley, Public Citizen's lead attorney 
in the Carlin case, wrote in paper posted on the group's Web site 
earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Department of Defense, one of the government's largest  
generators of computer records, has announced detailed plans to 
preserve and manage its electronic records in electronic format,'' 
Tankersley wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Other agencies also are guarding against premature destruction  
of electronic records, he wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	It was uncertain whether Public Citizen would appeal the loss.  
Tankersley did not immediately return a telephone call Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	His colleague in the case, Alan Morrison, told The Washington  
Post that a decision on a higher appeal had not been made. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990807.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 19:21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Flat Tire Finishes Armstrong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN SEBASTIAN, Spain (AP) -- Francesco Casagrande of Italy today  
won his second consecutive San Sebastian Classic, a World Cup 
cycling event. 
</P>
<P>
	A flat tire knocked out Tour de France winner Lance Armstrong.  
</P>
<P>
	The American dropped quit about 25 miles from the finish, after  
getting a puncture as he approached the traditionally decisive 
Jaizkibel mountain pass among the leading pack of cyclists. 
</P>
<P>
	The puncture apparently ended Amstrong's hopes of being among  
the leaders at the finish line and he decided to abandoned the race 
rather than change the wheel and carry on. 
</P>
<P>
	And, it was on the Jaizkibel pass that Casagrande opened up his  
lead, crossing the finishing line 43 seconds ahead of the pack of 
25 riders. Rik Verbrougghe of Belgium finished second, followed by 
Italy's Guiliano Figuera. 
</P>
<P>
	Casagrande covered the 143 miles in 5 hours, 15 minutes and 29  
seconds in the sixth of 10 one-day races making up cycling's World 
Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong had said the San Sebastian would be his last race of  
the European season. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's race was the first world class event since the Tour  
de France in July. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990807.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 19:21:23 </DATE_TIME>
