<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 11:26:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Americans Wins Bronze in Soccer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- It wasn't Mexico. It wasn't the  
Confederations Cup. It was another bronze medal. For the United 
States, that's major progress. 
</P>
<P>
	With a goal in each half, the United States overcame a driving  
rain, gusting wind, a hostile crowd and Canada to win 2-1 Friday 
night and take third place at the Pan American Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``With our youngsters, U.S. soccer has never been in as good  
shape as it is right now,'' U.S. coach Clive Charles said. 
</P>
<P>
	Carlos Bocanegra drove in a header off a cross from Cory Gibbs  
in the seventh minute. Then 17-year-old forward Landon Donovan of 
Bayer Leverkusen in Germany added a second off a rebound in the 
60th minute to give the United States only its third men's soccer 
medal in Pan American play. 
</P>
<P>
	Coming here with an amalgamated squad of under-17, under-20 and  
under-23 players, the United States admitted before the tournament 
began it came to Winnipeg to test prospects for the Olympic 
qualifying run next year. 
</P>
<P>
	The players had other ideas. They wanted a medal.  
</P>
<P>
	``You don't even know,'' Donovan said, unable to quantify the  
desire to get a medal despite the little hope observers gave them. 
``I'm just happy we won the game. That's all I care about. It's all 
about that bronze medal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The guys are going nuts,'' Charles said. ``They're very  
happy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bronze medal came only three days after the United States'  
senior team beat Saudi Arabia 2-0 in Mexico City to take third 
place at the Confederations Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Bocanegra's header from the 6-yard line came amid intermittent  
rain. But then the skies opened up with heavy rain and strong 
winds. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite a capacity crowd of about 8,000, Canada rarely  
threatened until the final 10 minutes. Chris Pozniak gave the host 
nation hope, launching a right-footer from just outside the arc 
past the outstretched arm of goalkeeper Tim Howard and into the 
upper right corner of the net in the 85th. 
</P>
<P>
	``They got up a goal early and we didn't play very well,''  
Canada coach Bruce Twamley said. ``They deserved it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990807.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 11:26:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
