<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Orleans Schools Call in Marine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- To fix schools where paint peels off  
classroom walls like snakeskin, where teachers bring their own 
toilet paper and where test scores are lower than the surrounding 
swamps, New Orleans has called in the Marines. 
</P>
<P>
	Actually, just one Marine -- Alphonse Davis, 48, a slender,  
bespectacled former colonel who left his job as a Pentagon division 
chief for a $150,000-a-year job in his home town. 
</P>
<P>
	Because he's never been a schoolteacher and has no education  
degrees, the state Board of Elementary and Secondary Education had 
to rewrite the rules for superintendents. It decreed Davis a CEO 
rather than a superintendent and told him he had to hire a No. 2 
with a background in education, by late October. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some call me superintendent, some call me colonel. To me, it  
doesn't matter,'' Davis says. He notes he's taught young Marines -- 
he ran the Officer Candidates School from 1995-97 -- and says his 
New Orleans job is to harness everyone's knowledge and enthusiasm. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm grateful for nay-sayers. It proves to me that people are  
interested and excited about education,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis' task is to rescue a school system many parents have  
already abandoned -- unless they have kids in one of the few magnet 
schools or can't afford to send them to private or parochial 
school. More than a fifth of the city's 106,000 students are in 
private schools. 
</P>
<P>
	``Make no mistake -- ours is a system in crisis,'' he told his  
new troops in his first communique last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis wears mufti these days, but his shoes still sport a high  
military gloss from his 26 years in the Marines and he still spouts 
the odd bit of mil-bizspeak. He won't appoint committees to find 
ways to improve schools, for instance -- he'll have Tiger Teams, 
``fast-strike'' crews that aim to get answers fast. 
</P>
<P>
	Terence Bradford, whose daughter just graduated from a New  
Orleans high school and has one son in high school and another in 
fourth grade, says he's impressed with what he's read about Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very optimistic. I think he's going to do a great job,''  
he says. 
</P>
<P>
	Any way you look at New Orleans' school system, it's a mess.  
</P>
<P>
	A few magnet schools are successful, but systemwide scores are  
abysmal. 
</P>
<P>
	One principal defended his students' standardized test scores by  
noting they were above the city average. Yet the city average was 
at the 26th percentile, which means it was lower than 74 percent of 
all U.S. students who took the test. 
</P>
<P>
	Statewide norms this spring were at the 44th or 45th percentile,  
depending on grade level. Orleans Parish norms were at the 23rd to 
25th percentile. 
</P>
<P>
	Even the successful schools aren't exempt from turmoil. Academic  
magnet schools are rewriting admissions policies because of 
allegations they discriminated against blacks. Supporters of the 
newly renovated arts magnet school want the state to take it over 
because they fear the cash-strapped city might not be able to keep 
it up. 
</P>
<P>
	The last superintendent, Morris Holmes, hired from Fort Worth,  
Texas, in 1993 as the system's savior, was bought out in 1997, just 
months after signing his second contract, because of a series of 
controversies that brought further scorn on the district. 
</P>
<P>
	They included reports that test scores might have been inflated,  
forfeiture of an $800,000 state grant because student expulsions 
were misreported and revelations that the district over five years 
had lost $3.4 million in property -- including computer monitors, 
sewing machines, a photocopier, automotive shop equipment, 10 air 
conditioners, three pianos and 450 bank instruments. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, a federal jury last year found that the Orleans  
Parish School Board had deliberately overcharged the U.S. 
Department of Education by $7.6 million in insurance costs over 11 
years, including Holmes' entire stint as superintendent. 
</P>
<P>
	On his first day on the job last month, Davis announced a  
100-day plan that includes Tiger Teams for reading, summer school, 
the discipline and dress code, and the state tests that decide 
whether students get promoted. The teams must have final reports in 
by Aug. 25. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan calls for students to write regular essays about books  
he chooses. It also proposes a ``Word of the Month'' program that 
involves essays and discussions about ``values-based'' words such 
as ``respect'' or ``discipline.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He's also proposed neighborhood homework centers staffed by  
volunteer college students and residents. 
</P>
<P>
	He says he'll get rid of people who aren't committed to change,  
even if they have contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	``Change is not going to happen overnight,'' warns Davis, an  
admitted sloganeer. ``Change and progress are evolutionary, not 
revolutionary.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
