<HEADLINE> Perez Withdraws Suspension Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Catcher Eddie Perez withdrew his appeal of a  
four-game suspension and will begin serving the penalty today when 
the Braves play the San Francisco Giants in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	Perez was suspended and fined $1,000 for triggering a brawl in a  
game with the Philadelphia Phillies last week. 
</P>
<P>
	The trouble began after Phillies pitcher Paul Byrd hit Perez in  
the third inning, the second time in less than a week that Byrd hit 
his former teammate with a pitch. 
</P>
<P>
	The following inning, the pair exchanged words when Byrd came to  
the plate. Perez threw a punch, setting off the brawl. 
</P>
<P>
	Braves manager Bobby Cox drew a two-game suspension, which he  
served, for his actions in the same game. Cox returned to the field 
after being ejected in the previous inning for arguing a 
double-play call. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he came back to restore order.  
</P>
<P>
	Perez will miss the final two games of the Giants' series and  
the start of a series with the Houston Astros. 
  	   	
