<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Aug. 7, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Gunmen Surround Russian Villages  
</P>
<P>
	MAKHACHKALA, Russia (AP) -- Russian helicopter gunships today  
attacked gunmen surrounding three villages in the troubled and 
violent Caucasus region, near the border of breakaway Chechnya. The 
militants crossed from Chechnya into Dagestan early today and took 
up positions around the villages of Ansalta and Rakhata, Interior 
Ministry officials said. The rebel group has said it wants to merge 
the republics into one Islamic state. The gunmen appeared to be 
from the fundamentalist Wahhabi Islamic movement, which has been 
active in Chechnya and Dagestan since the 1994 launch of Chechnya's 
war for independence. Chechnya won de facto independence from 
Russia in the war, though Moscow still claims it is part of Russia. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Aims To Eliminate Poverty  
</P>
<P>
	HELENA, Ark. (AP) -- President Clinton today promised to devote  
the rest of his term to eliminating the poverty that clings to this 
neglected corner of his home state and other parts of the 
Mississippi delta region, where unemployment is twice the national 
average. Clinton stopped in Helena for a private meeting with 54 
local officials, who are organizing a commission to take on the 
enormous problems of the Delta, from education to housing and civic 
infrastructure. The president submitted his so-called ``new 
markets'' legislative proposal to Congress last week. It includes a 
series of tax incentives and lending guarantees for new investment. 

</P>
<P>
	Black Gets S. African Bank Post  
</P>
<P>
	JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- South Africa's all-important  
central bank today was placed in the hands of Tito Mboweni, moving 
forward the country's transformation from a white-dominated land to 
a multiracial society. Mboweni, a former labor minister, becomes 
Reserve Bank governor while most of South Africa's majority blacks 
remain mired in poverty five years after apartheid collapsed. 
Mboweni shoved aside notions that the Reserve Bank should 
accelerate the transformation of South Africa from a society where 
only whites had privilege to one where opportunity awaited 
everyone, saying: ``Our role is to ensure there is a stable 
financial environment. Our mandate is very narrow.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Governors Wary of Tax Cut Plan  
</P>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Republican governors meeting today warned that  
they will not let GOP lawmakers raid state budgets to pay for the 
GOP's congressional tax cut plan. Several governors accused fellow 
Republicans in Washington of trying to renege on pledges to ship 
the money to states. They suggested the development could damage 
their promised partnership with Washington. Republican 
congressional leaders have considered asking the nation's governors 
to return up to $6 billion in welfare money to help balance the 
books on their 10-year, $792 billion tax cut proposal. 

</P>
<P>
	Bomb Hurled at Israeli Soldiers  
</P>
<P>
	HEBRON, West Bank (AP) -- Attackers threw a gasoline bomb into an  
Israeli army jeep today, injuring two soldiers and further 
aggravating the region's ethnic tensions. The incident occurred in 
the Israeli-controlled sector of this tensely divided West Bank 
city, where two Jewish settlers were injured Tuesday, apparently by 
militant Palestinian gunmen. Since then the area's 30,000 
Palestinians have been barred from leaving or entering Hebron, and 
have been kept in their homes by a curfew. There have been several 
clashes between Israeli troops and Palestinian stone throwers on 
the region's dividing line in the past few days. 

</P>
<P>
	Boggs Homers for 3,000th Hit  
</P>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Wade Boggs became the first player  
to homer for his 3,000th hit, connecting in the sixth inning for a 
two-run shot tonight against Cleveland. Boggs reached his lifelong 
goal and celebrated with an emotional trip around the bases. Boggs 
pointed upwards -- a tribute to his mother, killed in a 1986 car 
accident -- as he became the 23rd player to get 3,000 hits. A few 
steps from home, Boggs again pointed up. He then got down on his 
knees and kissed home plate as his teammates waited to embrace him. 

</P>
<P>
	Johansson Reaches du Maurier Final  
</P>
<P>
	MONTREAL (AP) -- Thomas Johansson of Sweden, seeded 11th,  
advanced to the final of the $2.45 million du Maurier Open men's 
tennis tournament today with a 4-6, 6-1, 6-3 victory over 
ninth-seeded Nicolas Kiefer of Germany. Johansson advances to face 
the winner of today's other semifinal matching Andre Agassi and 
Yevgeny Kafelnikov of Russia. In the semifinals, Johansson came in 
fresh from having played an early match the day before while Kiefer 
was still recovering from a late-night, three-set victory over 
top-seeded Patrick Rafter of Australia. Johansson now stands one 
victory away from the biggest victory of his career. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY FOSS  
  	   	
</P>
