<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rodriguez Sparks Yankee-Mariner Brawl </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- The New York Yankees knew what to expect when  
Frankie Rodriguez stood on the mound and Jose Mesa was watching 
from the bullpen in the ninth inning for the Seattle Mariners. 
</P>
<P>
	After New York's Jason Grimsley was ejected the previous inning  
for hitting Edgar Martinez, Rodriguez -- who triggered a brawl at 
Dodger Stadium last month by throwing a pitch at Mark 
Grudzielanek's head -- took the mound to start the ninth Friday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mesa is pitching that ninth inning, no doubt about it,'' New  
York's Chad Curtis said. ``OK, all of a sudden, Mesa's not out 
there. Rodriguez is back out there. So they left Rodriguez out 
there so he could get tossed instead of Mesa.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rodriguez, who was claimed off the waiver wire by the  
pitching-short Mariners on May 26, became the focal point of 
Seattle's second on-the-field fight in less than a month on Friday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	In an 11-8 victory by New York, he hit the Yankees' second  
batter in the ninth, Chuck Knoblauch, with a pitch and then, after 
being taken out by manager Lou Piniella, went after New York 
catcher Joe Girardi, who was the next batter. 
</P>
<P>
	The benches and bullpens emptied with some of the Yankees intent  
to get Rodriguez, who knocked Girardi down with two punches. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you watch the replay, you'll see (Mariners catcher Dan)  
Wilson on the first pitch to Chuck tap his hands on the grounds 
like give me the curveball in the dirt this time so that he can hit 
him with the second pitch fastball,'' Curtis said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He throws second-pitch fastball and it hits him in the rear  
end. If his manager tells him to hit a guy, you hit him in the rear 
end. The guy did his job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It didn't end there because the Yankees were up and screaming in  
their dugout for plate umpire Gary Cederstrom to throw Rodriguez 
out, too. 
</P>
<P>
	New York's Derek Jeter did not play Friday night after being hit  
in the left wrist by a pitch by Jose Paniagua in Thursday night's 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	``They instigated it,'' Piniella said. ``It was their pitcher  
that hit Edgar after he gave up a home run (to Alex Rodriguez) and 
it was obvious and it was blatant. What are we supposed to do? We 
did what we had to do and hit one of their players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Piniella said the Mariners didn't hit Jeter on purpose.  
</P>
<P>
	``There is no connection,'' he said. ``There should be no  
connection at all. Jeter wasn't hit intentionally. Edgar was hit 
intentionally. It was obvious.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rodriguez did some screaming at the Yankees as he was leaving  
the field, too. The screaming escalated into his charging Girardi. 
</P>
<P>
	``What he should have done was just go off the field,'' Curtis  
said. ``He did his job. He did what he was supposed to do. He had 
the respect of his team and he had the respect of our team for 
doing that. Why didn't he just go off the field? You don't need to 
incite anything by screaming.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During the melee that followed, Safeco Field's first brawl since  
replacing the Kingdome as the Mariners' home July 15, Yankees coach 
Don Zimmer, 68, fell to the ground and then stumbled to his feet, 
looking dazed. 
</P>
<P>
	And Bernie Williams, the Yankees' center fielder who hit one of  
four homers off Mariners starter Jeff Fassero, broke loose of 
Wilson and chased Rodriguez to the Seattle dugout. 
</P>
<P>
	``I couldn't get up,'' said Zimmer, who almost left the team  
earlier this season because of chronic knee problems. ``My leg gave 
out on me and hurt a little bit and I was out of breath.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No players were injured seriously in the fight. The Mariners  
lost Brian Hunter and Charles Gipson, both outfielders, with 
injuries in the Dodgers' brawl. In that game, Mariners Jay Buhner, 
Damaso Marte, Mesa and Paniagua were ejected. 
</P>
<P>
	In Friday night's fight, Zimmer and Girardi were ejected.  
Afterward, Girardi was not in a forgiving mood. 
</P>
<P>
	``He (Rodriguez) tried to hurt me and I'm not going to going to  
forget it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Yankees manager Joe Torre watched the brawl on TV from his  
office after tossed by first-base umpire Doug Eddings in the eighth 
for arguing too strongly on a play at first. He held his breath. 
</P>
<P>
	``You talk about ending careers. It could happen in a  
heartbeat,'' Torre said. ``It was really ugly, but I guess ESPN 
will have something to lead with.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
