<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oolong, Campbell Wins Oaks Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Oolong came roaring down the  
stretch today to give Hall of Fame driver John Campbell his first 
win in the $500,000 Hambletonian Oaks at the Meadowlands. 
</P>
<P>
	Campbell, who has won five Hambletonians, took his first Oaks by  
swinging Oolong wide at the top of the stretch and letting her pass 
five fillies for a 1 1/2-length win in a career-best 1:54.4. 
</P>
<P>
	Loveelytobehold set the early pace through relatively slow early  
fraction of 28.3 seconds and 56.4 before being caught by the 
$16,000 purchase out of Armbro Goal by China Tea. 
</P>
<P>
	The Per Hendricksen-trained filly, paid $5.40, $3.80 and $3 as  
the favorite. Lovelytobehold held second while Bit O Candy finished 
third. 
</P>
<P>
	French Panicure won the $400,000 Mistletoe Shalee pace for  
3-year old fillies with a late burst of speed that carried her past 
Beach Crystal and Marfa Hanover to a length victory in a career 
best 1:50.4. 
</P>
<P>
	Driven by George Brennan, trained by Brett Pelling and owned by  
Bob Glazer, French Penicure was third in the top of the stretch 
before closing. She paid $17 to increase her lifetime earnings to 
$338,814. 
</P>
<P>
	Red Bow Tie swung three-wide and came charging down the stretch  
for Luc Ouellette to successfully defend the $131,000 U.S. Pacing 
championship in 1:48.4. He paid $4.20. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Galleria ($8.60) took an early lead and set a world  
record of 1:49.1 in winning the $100,000 invitational for mares 
with Brennan. 
</P>
<P>
	In the $424,000 Nat Ray Final, a one mile free for all trot,  
Magician held off a late bid by Supergrit to win by a half length 
in 1:52.4. The Earl Cruise-trained gelding was driven by David 
Miller and paid $18.20. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
