<DOCNO> APW19990807.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 03:00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Browns' Couch Ready for Prime Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEREA, Ohio (AP) -- Whether it was as a Kentucky high school  
football sensation or as the No. 1 pick in the NFL draft, Tim Couch 
has always been in the spotlight. 
</P>
<P>
	But never in one as bright as he'll step into Monday night.  
</P>
<P>
	``My first game in the NFL,'' said the Cleveland Browns rookie  
quarterback. ``To me, it's like the Super Bowl.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This year's Hall of Fame Game in Canton, Ohio, against the  
Dallas Cowboys is like the Super Bowl to all of Cleveland, which 
has waited three years for the Browns' return. And when the Browns 
take the field for the first time, a new football era will dawn in 
football-mad Northeast Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fans here are unbelievable,'' Couch said. ``Their support  
before we've even played a game has been unreal. This is an 
exciting time for all of us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Cleveland, it's more than an exhibition opener. It's  
history. 
</P>
<P>
	For the new Browns, the game will be gauge of how far they've  
come in two weeks of training camp, and how far they'll need to go 
to get ready for the Pittsburgh Steelers in the regular-season 
opener Sept. 12. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have butterflies right now,'' said Browns coach Chris  
Palmer, who like Couch, will be making his NFL debut. ``Hopefully, 
we'll be organized, have our heads in the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Couch is the Browns QB of the future, and he'll come into  
Monday's game after Ty Detmer, the QB of the present, runs 12 to 15 
plays with the first-team offense. Couch will then work with the 
first unit, and play the second half of the second quarter with the 
second team. 
</P>
<P>
	He'll remain in the game for part of the third quarter before  
third-stringer Mike Cook takes over. Palmer asked Couch and Detmer 
to give him a list of 10 or 12 plays each feels comfortable 
running. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are some fairly aggressive plays,'' Couch said, ``and  
there are some real high-percentage plays just to get me started. 
Hopefully, we can get a couple of deep passes in there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Browns have $59.4 million and seven years invested in Couch,  
and they're eager to see how their franchise player has developed. 
</P>
<P>
	Couch has been impressive. Like every rookie, he was initially  
overwhelmed and seemed to have trouble adjusting to the speed of 
the pro game. 
</P>
<P>
	``You hand the ball off and you look back and see a big hole  
open up and how quickly it closes is phenomenal,'' he said. ``It 
looks like a play is going for 40 yards, and ... Bam! Here comes 
somebody to make the play at the line of scrimmage. 
</P>
<P>
	Couch said his confidence is growing by the day, and it shows.  
He looks poised under pressure and has shown he can improvise, 
sidestepping rushers to sidearm passes or looking off a covered 
receiver and throwing to his secondary target. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first day of training camp the guys were just flying by  
me, everything was so fast here. Now everything has slowed down 
just a little bit where I can settle in and make the throws.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During a recent scrimmage, Couch, tripped while backpedaling by  
one of his offensive guards, completed a 15-yard pass down field 
while laying flat on his back. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's looked good,'' Palmer said. ``He's worked hard and  
continues make good progress.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Couch has been working overtime to be ready for the day he's  
called upon to lead the Browns for good. He spends hours after 
practice going over the Browns' thick playbook. 
</P>
<P>
	He studies a play, traces the passing routes over in his  
notebook. Studies it, and then does it again. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike some of the other rookie quarterbacks around the league  
who have held out, Couch came to camp signed and ready to play. He 
thinks that has helped him focus, and may have won him some fans 
among his teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	``With me being here on time, it went over well with guys,'' he  
said. ``I've been here working hard and just trying to fit in. And 
I think they've just accepted me as a regular guy.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
