<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Winfield Excels At Corner for Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FREDONIA, N.Y. (AP) -- The Buffalo Bills didn't hear the whispers  
that 5-foot-8 Antoine Winfield was too small to play cornerback in 
the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, they're glad their hearing wasn't real sharp.  
</P>
<P>
	The Bills' top draft choice and Thorpe Award winner as the  
nation's top defensive back has stood taller than his critics, not 
to mention a few receivers. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a natural at corner,'' Bills safety and eight-year  
veteran Kurt Schulz said in training camp Saturday. ``He's quick 
and aggressive, he's smooth. He can play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Winfield was one of the top deep coverage defenders in college  
and a hard hitter who could help stop the run and also blitz. 
Drafted 23rd overall behind Georgia's Champ Bailey and Arizona's 
Chris McAlister, Winfield already has shown the Bills almost 
everything, except for one thing -- hitting. 
</P>
<P>
	And that's only because there has been none of that allowed yet,  
to Winfield's disappointment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought we should have done some tackling before we had our  
first preseason game at Seattle next weekend,'' Winfield said after 
Saturday's non-contact scrimmage. ``But that's up to the coaches. 
I'm just here to do what they want.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What the Bills want is for Winfield to provide the kind of deep  
coverage that allowed him to take a top receiver out of the game 
all by himself. 
</P>
<P>
	They also expect him to provide run support. Winfield had 75  
stops and two sacks for the Buckeyes in 1998, coming off a 
100-tackle season in 1997. ``He's the best overall cornerback I've 
ever had,'' OSU coach John Cooper said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically in college I was known for tackling,'' Winfield  
said. ``They want me more as a cover man up here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lack of height doesn't add up to lack of might in Winfield's  
case. ``That's not a factor,'' he said. ``I'm a ballplayer. I can 
match up with these guys. I'm doing pretty well, no complaints from 
the coaches. I'm not worried about the height issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Winfield and Tennessee standout Peerless Price, the Buffalo  
Bills' top draft picks, needed no introduction at training camp. 
They both grew up in Ohio, Winfield in Akron and Price in Dayton, 
and they met in a high school all-star game. 
</P>
<P>
	They also met in the Citrus Bowl after the 1995 season when both  
were freshmen. The Vols beat Ohio State 20-14. ``He's a good 
corner,'' Price said. ``He has quick feet and is able to backpedal 
really fast.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ken Irvin, who finally nailed down a full-time position as a  
starter at left cornerback last season following the departure of 
free agent Jeff Burris, knows all about the tough challenges 
Winfield faces. 
</P>
<P>
	``At Ohio State, people really weren't coming at him,'' Irvin  
said. ``In this league, nobody's really fearful of going at 
corners, so he's going to get balls caught on him and he has to 
come back from those and not get in a slump. But he has all the 
tools, no question.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Winfield's weaknesses, besides his alleged lack of height, are  
said to be that he tends to bite on play action, and doesn't always 
find the ball instinctively. He did not intercept a pass in his 
last season at OSU. 
</P>
<P>
	But he's meeting his challenges face-to-face, literally. ``You  
have to get your hands on these receivers; they'll run right by 
you, and the quarterbacks put the ball right there,'' Winfield 
said. ``I'm kind of getting used to how fast the game is and 
receivers' routes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Winfield, whose five-year $7 million contract includes a  
$3.5-million signing bonus, is settling in. He quickly bought a 
house in Orchard Park, where the Bills play. 
</P>
<P>
	He's just a few hours down the turnpike from his family in  
Akron. He has a son and is engaged, but hasn't set a date for the 
wedding. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not quite ready yet,'' he said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
