<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soccer Hooligans Use Web for Trouble </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARDIFF, Wales (AP) -- The English soccer season got off to a  
violent start as fans of division two clubs, Cardiff City and 
Millwall, fought in the city today after apparently arranging the 
clashes via the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Fourteen people were hurt and six arrested during a day of  
violence as Cardiff followers fought some of the 700 Millwall 
supporters who went to the game. 
</P>
<P>
	According to police, shoppers cowered in terror as rival gangs  
of hooligans battled in the center of the city. 
</P>
<P>
	An Internet bulletin board contained a number of references to  
the Cardiff City-Millwall match, including details of where the 
violence would start and even a running commentary on the fighting. 
</P>
<P>
	One message said the fighting had begun and added, ``Don't miss  
the tear-up of the year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another suggested a rendezvous for any hooligans looking for a  
fight: ``11 o'clock Cardiff Central, where we go from there its up 
to u.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, the National Criminal Intelligence Service  
published its annual report, which highlighted the dangers posed by 
organized gangs of thugs using the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The report, which showed the first rise in the number of arrests  
for soccer hooliganism in six years, said violent fans were 
becoming more organized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990807.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 00:20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Boxer Wins Gold at Pan Am </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Gerald Tucker stood on the medal  
stand, a notch above the other top finishers, and it was there that 
his achievement took a tug at his emotions. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was coming onto me that I had won a gold medal. It was  
coming slowly but surely, and I was feeling it,'' said Tucker, who 
put his hand over his mouth as his eyes got teary. 
</P>
<P>
	``No doubt this is my biggest win ever. I'll never forget this,  
not for the rest of my life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tucker, of Cincinnati, scored a lopsided 15-3 victory Friday  
night over Venezuela's Neouar Cermeno in the bantamweight finals on 
a night when Cuban boxers claimed five gold medals. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the Cuban victories came at the expense of American  
Arthur Palac, who lost the middleweight championship to a 
showboating Yohason Martinez of Cuba 12-7. 
</P>
<P>
	Two more U.S. boxers, flyweight Jose Navarro of Los Angeles and  
super heavyweight Davin King of Temple Hills, Md., will go after 
gold medals tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	Tucker, 20, was as surprised as anyone that the score was so  
one-sided against his taller opponent. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had my hands up, but I was like running into a lot of shots.  
I don't know if it was knocking my head back or not. But I know I 
was feeling punches in there, more than three. So I didn't think it 
was lopsided,'' Tucker said. 
</P>
<P>
	An Olympic alternate in 1996, Tucker finished second in two  
other tournaments this year. His nerves were racing as he prepared 
for the fight of his life. Then he let his quickness and instincts 
take over. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-4, 165-pound Palac had to contend with Martinez, who  
danced around the ring with his hands down most of the night. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically his style is typical of a Cuban boxer who is kind of  
cocky,'' Palac said. ``He was a little cocky and I let that take 
control of me a little bit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Palac, of Hamtramck, Mich., was bothered by a sore shoulder, but  
said winning the silver medal has prepared him for Olympic 
qualifying. He'd like another shot at Martinez in about 13 months. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll just wait until I meet him in 2000 at Sydney,'' Palac  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuban Maikro Romero beat Mexico's Liboria Romero 8-4 to win the  
light flyweight gold. And in the lightweight title match, Cuba's 
Mario Kindelan scored with a left jab in the final 15 seconds to 
edge Canadian Dana Laframboise 2-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Canadian welterweight Jeremy Molitor lost a tough decision to  
1996 Olympic silver medalist Juan Hernandez. The score was tied 1-1 
after four rounds, so it was decided on a punch callback, in which 
the scores of the two judges who have awarded the most and least 
blows are thrown out. The number of blows recorded by the three 
remaining judges are then added and Hernandez was declared a 19-7 
winner. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuban heavyweight Odlaniel Solis made it a near-sweep with a 4-2  
win over Mark Simmons of Canada. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990807.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 19:23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Gives Gore Campaign Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore may be concerned  
about being perceived as too close to a president who was 
impeached, but that is not stopping him from using Bill Clinton's 
fund-raising prowess to boost his White House hopes. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton lavished praise on Gore at a Saturday night fund-raiser  
for the Gore 2000 presidential campaign committee, the first of a 
series of such events featuring the president. He also will attend 
four Gore fund-raisers in the nation's capital, two next week and 
two on Sept. 22. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have been with this man in every conceivable kind of  
circumstance,'' Clinton said. ``I know him as few people do. If 
everything was on the line and I had to pick an American to make a 
decision ... I would pick Al Gore, and so should you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Now there's a real friend for you,'' Gore said. He pitched an  
agenda heavy on improving health care and education, then made his 
own shameless appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	``I need your help,'' Gore said. ``I need your vote. I want your  
vote, your support, and everything you can do to convince people to 
be for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During an outreach meeting with about 200 black ministers prior  
to the fund-raiser, Clinton promised to help Gore unconditionally, 
in part to repay the loyalty Gore showed during the impeachment. 
</P>
<P>
	``For a long time now, he's been at my back, and I intend to be  
with his,'' Clinton said. He called Gore ``a good and decent man,'' 
and predicted Gore would go down in history as one of most 
influential vice presidents to ever hold the job. 
</P>
<P>
	``An election is a job interview. He wants you to hire him,''  
Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do, I do,'' Gore interjected amid peals of laughter.  
</P>
<P>
	``And all of these other people that are running are perfectly  
nice people, but all of them are saying, 'Hire us too, we want to 
be president, and sooner or later we'll get around to telling you 
why,''' Clinton continued. ``You already know more about him than 
anybody else running.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's dinner at the State House Convention Center drew  
about 500 of Arkansas' most influential Democrats, with each asked 
to contribute at least $500. Other scheduled speakers included Sen. 
Blanche Lincoln, D-Ark.; U.S. Transportation Secretary Rodney 
Slater and Arkansas Attorney General Mark Pryor. 
</P>
<P>
	Privately, Gore has told associates he had felt the drag of  
Clinton's impeachment on attempts to get his own campaign in gear 
during the first half of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore campaign officials said last week they were confident the  
public was well past any unease about Clinton and his personal 
behavior. But it was clear Saturday that public pairings of Clinton 
and Gore were planned carefully so they would not come across as a 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	The vice president arrived in Little Rock separately from  
Clinton, flying in from Chicago where he was speaking to a meeting 
of the Rainbow Coalition. Clinton and Gore were appearing together 
for a private meeting with farmers and African-American ministers 
before the fund-raising dinner. 
</P>
<P>
	They met with about 75 farmers at a coffee house near the  
Arkansas River, shedding their blue jackets while they chatted with 
the casually dressed farmers about an array of problems, including 
subsidized rice from Japan and subsidized cotton from China. Both 
crops are grown in Arkansas. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore proclaimed the current farm bill ``badly broken'' and  
Clinton said he would try to keep Congress in session all year if 
necessary to fix it. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's campaign has stressed that the president plays no  
hands-on role in stump strategy -- even as the campaign takes 
advantage of Clinton's ability to invigorate Democrats in the face 
of a primary challenge from Sen. Bill Bradley, and the possibility 
of a tough race against the Republican front-runner, Texas Gov. 
George W. Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Clinton strategist Paul Begala, who is supporting Gore  
from the sidelines, said Gore only stands to benefit from having 
Clinton in his corner, in terms of fund raising and putting the 
full force of presidential power behind Gore's policy ideas. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think people are going to say, 'Clinton cheated on his  
wife, so let's go back to Reaganomics and give more tax cuts to the 
rich,''' Begala said. ``And that's exactly what the other side, the 
Republicans would do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Bradley team watched Gore and Clinton with little  
noticeable interest. 
</P>
<P>
	``All presidential elections are about the future and people are  
going to make a judgment of who they want for the future, not so 
much a calculation about the past,'' said Bradley spokesman Eric 
Hauser. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990807.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 19:23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Gives Gore Campaign Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore may be concerned  
about being perceived as too close to a president who was 
impeached, but that is not stopping him from using Bill Clinton's 
fund-raising prowess to boost his White House hopes. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton lavished praise on Gore at a Saturday night fund-raiser  
for the Gore 2000 presidential campaign committee, the first of a 
series of such events featuring the president. He also will attend 
four Gore fund-raisers in the nation's capital, two next week and 
two on Sept. 22. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have been with this man in every conceivable kind of  
circumstance,'' Clinton said. ``I know him as few people do. If 
everything was on the line and I had to pick an American to make a 
decision ... I would pick Al Gore, and so should you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Now there's a real friend for you,'' Gore said. He pitched an  
agenda heavy on improving health care and education, then made his 
own shameless appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	``I need your help,'' Gore said. ``I need your vote. I want your  
vote, your support, and everything you can do to convince people to 
be for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During an outreach meeting with about 200 black ministers prior  
to the fund-raiser, Clinton promised to help Gore unconditionally, 
in part to repay the loyalty Gore showed during the impeachment. 
</P>
<P>
	``For a long time now, he's been at my back, and I intend to be  
with his,'' Clinton said. He called Gore ``a good and decent man,'' 
and predicted Gore would go down in history as one of most 
influential vice presidents to ever hold the job. 
</P>
<P>
	``An election is a job interview. He wants you to hire him,''  
Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do, I do,'' Gore interjected amid peals of laughter.  
</P>
<P>
	``And all of these other people that are running are perfectly  
nice people, but all of them are saying, 'Hire us too, we want to 
be president, and sooner or later we'll get around to telling you 
why,''' Clinton continued. ``You already know more about him than 
anybody else running.'' 
</P>
