<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 13:22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Fired 32 for Misconduct in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of FBI employees fired for  
misconduct rose from 19 to 32 between 1997 and 1998. The bureau 
says swifter completion of more internal investigations was the 
cause. 
</P>
<P>
	In its annual report Friday, the bureau's Office of Professional  
Responsibility said that 301 employees received discipline ranging 
from oral reprimands to dismissal in 1998, compared with 212 the 
preceding year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is premature to describe the increase as a trend,'' the  
FBI's internal watchdog office said. ``The increase in employees 
disciplined is attributable in part to increased efficiency in the 
disciplinary process'' because more agents were assigned to the 
watchdog office. 
</P>
<P>
	The expanded office completed 528 investigations during 1998,  
compared to only 399 in 1997. The report also said the backlog of 
cases open for more than a year was reduced from 24.3 percent of 
the outstanding total at the end of fiscal 1997 to 16.7 percent at 
the end of fiscal 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	In one of the most notable 1998 cases, special agent Daron  
Council of New Orleans was accused of attempting to extort money 
from a drug dealer. After an investigation, Council was arrested, 
fired and pleaded guilty to two counts of soliciting and accepting 
a bribe. He was sentenced to 16 months in prison and fined $3,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Other FBI employees were fired for lying to internal  
investigators, unauthorized disclosures, unprofessional conduct, 
misuse of government property, drunk driving, drug abuse, sexual 
harassment, misuse of a bureau position, theft or embezzlement of 
government property and other crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	The 301 employees disciplined in 1998 represented just under  
half the 615 employees whose investigations for serious misconduct 
were completed that year. The 301 include 140 agents and 161 
support workers and comprise 1.1 percent of the bureau's total 
workforce. Of the 32 fired, 11 were agents and 21 support workers. 
</P>
<P>
	By comparison, the 212 disciplined in 1997 included 99 agents  
and 113 support workers and comprised 0.8 percent of the workforce 
that year. 
</P>
<P>
	During 1998, six employees were demoted, 60 were suspended  
without pay for 15 or more days, 94 were suspended without pay for 
14 or fewer days, five were put on probation, 64 were censured, and 
40 received oral reprimands. 
</P>
<P>
	An increasing number of allegations of domestic violence by FBI  
workers is being reported as more and more local police use arrests 
rather than conciliation to resolve such incidents, the Office of 
Professional Responsibility said. ``Allegations regarding such 
abuse have included agent and support employees, males and females, 
spouses and unmarried persons and children.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The report, which was distributed to all FBI employees, warned:  
``A criminal assault in the home is conduct far beneath the 
standards the FBI expects of its employees and is treated as 
serious misconduct. ... Discipline may be imposed even if a local 
criminal conviction does not result.'' 
</P>
<P>
	FBI Director Louis Freeh has more than doubled the staff at the  
Office of Professional Responsibility since 1997, and Justice 
Department Inspector General Michael Bromwich said last week it has 
become more professional. But Bromwich said the bureau needs a 
permanent outside watchdog agency whose investigations he said 
would have greater deterrent effect and more public credibility 
than internal reviews. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990807.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 10:30:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Freud Changed Way We Look at Things </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- One hundred years ago, a 43-year-old Viennese  
neurologist produced a book with an intriguing claim: that dreams 
express our hidden desires. Despite its vivid prose and frank talk 
about sex, almost no one read it. Six years after publication, 
``The Interpretation of Dreams'' had sold only 351 copies. 
</P>
<P>
	But the author, Sigmund Freud, started a conversation, and we  
haven't stopped talking since. 
</P>
<P>
	``Insight such as this falls to one's lot but once in a  
lifetime,'' Freud himself observed later. 
</P>
<P>
	After a century of Freud, you can blame him or thank him, laugh  
or lie down, but a couch may never again be just a couch. Never 
again will we look at ourselves and each other in quite the same 
way. 
</P>
<P>
	He took us inward. He gave us the talking cure, a technique he  
called ``psychoanalysis'' that uses free association, dream 
interpretation and the patient's response to the analyst to explore 
the mind. A father of three boys and three girls, Freud plumbed the 
child's-eye view to find the core of the adult. If our dreams 
tumble with secrets exposed, he said, awake we're driven by 
conflicts deep in the unconscious. 
</P>
<P>
	Nothing is accidental. Everything has meaning. Freedom comes  
when we know how we were shaped by the past -- that's the goal of 
psychoanalysis. 
</P>
<P>
	There have been doubters from the start -- the most basic  
criticism that there's simply no proof that Freud's methods work. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even if people get better, that doesn't mean they get better  
because of the treatment,'' said Adolf Grunbaum, a leading Freud 
skeptic who is a philosopher of science and a research professor of 
psychiatry at the University of Pittsburgh. Grunbaum respects 
Freud's genius but says he generalized too much and claimed credit 
as originator of ideas from antiquity. 
</P>
<P>
	Original or not, Freud's work swept away old views of how the  
mind works and brought new insights into mental illness. 
</P>
<P>
	Before Freud's time, the mentally ill were lucky if they didn't  
get locked away in an asylum, where shackles and beatings were 
common, said his biographer, historian Peter Gay, who runs the 
Center for Scholars and Writers at the New York Public Library. 
</P>
<P>
	An alternative, usually available only to the wealthy, was  
sometimes called moral treatment or moral therapy. This was found 
in country retreats that offered mainly rest, exercise, nourishing 
food and a lot of talking. ``Above all, being gentle with them,'' 
Gay said. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people were just neglected or just let go. These are  
the crazy eccentrics you read about in Dickens,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	And after Freud?  
</P>
<P>
	Just listen. Everyday talk bubbles with words from the  
psychological lexicon: psyche out, obsessive, compulsive, 
repressed, oedipal, well-adjusted, manic. 
</P>
<P>
	We're urged to talk about our feelings. We fantasize. We  
project. We're in denial. We internalize. We grow paranoid with 
anxiety. We're on guard against subliminal messages in advertising. 
We suppress urges when our inner child threatens to get us in 
trouble by acting out. 
</P>
<P>
	A newsletter for investors advises those suddenly enriched by a  
windfall: ``Maintaining our former sense of self might be difficult 
and important relationships are likely to change. ... if you decide 
not to work, will you be able to feel good about yourself?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Flocks of counselors offer psychological rescue for whole towns  
after traumas such as school shootings and deadly weather. Project 
Heartland, funded by government to provide counseling after the 
1995 Oklahoma City bombing, offered the same service when tornadoes 
ripped through the Midwest this year. Tipper Gore, the vice 
president's wife, led a recent White House conference to dispel 
myths about people who suffer from mental illness. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not all serious.  
</P>
<P>
	The ``Peanuts'' comic strip character Lucy dispenses psychiatric  
help at 5 cents a pop. Robert DeNiro plays a mobster with 
trigger-anxiety and Billy Crystal plays his therapist in the comedy 
movie ``Analyze This.'' But then, show business has always loved 
Freud. Check out ``Lady in the Dark,'' a Broadway musical turned 
into a 1944 movie starring Ginger Rogers as a magazine editor who 
undergoes analysis to decide among three beaux, with music by Kurt 
Weill and Ira Gershwin. 
</P>
<P>
	There was even a 1962 Hollywood biography, ``Freud,'' with  
Montgomery Clift in the title role. 
</P>
<P>
	Sigmund Freud was born May 6, 1856, in what is now the Czech  
Republic, and lived in Vienna most of his life. His home is a 
museum and he's a revered national figure in Austria. He died Sept. 
23, 1939, in London, a refugee from the Nazis, who burned the books 
of the atheist Jew. An 83-year-old man with cancer of the jaw, he 
asked for a fatal dose of morphine. 
</P>
<P>
	In the late 1800s, his research into neurology had drawn him to  
study hysteria -- strange symptoms of distress, like paralyzed limbs 
with no physical cause. This led him toward the mind. The Victorian 
period was waning, sex was back in vogue. Then World War I put a 
focus on aggression. Freud concluded the two drives were basic. 
</P>
<P>
	A writer of clear and powerful prose, Freud reached  
practitioners and public alike. He organized a movement to spread 
his theories. 
</P>
<P>
	Timing, good writing and promotion. ``Those three coalesced,''  
said Michael Roth, curator of the Library of Congress exhibit 
``Sigmund Freud: Conflict and Culture'' now at the Jewish Museum in 
New York and headed to Vienna and Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Freud applied his theories to other fields. He analyzed society  
and history, religion and art, morality and politics. 
</P>
<P>
	By midcentury, his influence and stature were clear -- placing  
him, according to one scholar's choice published in 1949, third 
among the 10 ``greats of our time,'' after Mohandas Gandhi and 
Albert Einstein. 
</P>
<P>
	The '50s and '60s were Freud's heyday in America.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was the only show in town,'' said Rosemarie Sand, a retired  
psychoanalyst in White Plains, N.Y. ``It was the answer to 
everything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since the 1970s, Freudian psychoanalysis, a process that may  
involve several sessions each week and take years, has been 
eclipsed in popularity by other forms of less costly and intensive 
psychotherapy and by drugs. Employers and health insurers no longer 
want to pay for unlimited therapy and many people lack the time or 
inclination. 
</P>
<P>
	Arguments over Freud continue to rage. Witness the controversy  
over the Library of Congress show, which opened last year in 
Washington after a two-year delay. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers blamed a lack of funding, but concern that it would  
be worshipful and one-sided prompted historian Peter Swales to 
circulate a petition in which 50 scholars and critics urged that 
the exhibit ``adequately reflect the full spectrum of informed 
opinion about the status of Freud's contribution to intellectual 
history.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Curator Roth, associate director of the Getty Research Institute  
for the History of Art and the Humanities in Los Angeles, said he 
had intended to consult Freud's critics before the petition, but 
the controversy made him more sensitive to it. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, emblazoned above the displays of letters and  
diaries and drafts in Freud's fluid, uphill script, are statements 
like feminist Germaine Greer's acid observation in 1970: ``Freud is 
the father of psychoanalysis. It had no mother.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview, Swales questioned the entire discipline that  
Freud fathered. ``What are the benefits of 100 years of 
psychoanalysis?'' he said, speaking from his home in New York. The 
field that probes the mind is subject to fads, he said, noting 
current enthusiasm for drugs like Prozac, the world's best-selling 
antidepressant. ``The field of psychiatry is overpopulated with 
fashion victims.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1970s, feminists were among those who brought Freud down  
from his pedestal, ridiculing ideas such as his theory that women 
are destined to be unhappy because they lack the physical apparatus 
of males. 
</P>
<P>
	``Women are quite right about Freud,'' said Mrs. Sand.  
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to a female friend Freud famously asked, ``What does  
a woman want?'' What a woman wants, said Mrs. Sand, is equal rights 
and fair treatment. ``Nowadays, your typical analyst, he's not 
going to hit her with penis envy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Decades earlier, Karen Horney, a prominent German-American  
psychiatrist, called Freud's theories on femininity male fantasy. 
</P>
<P>
	Freud ``did make a great contribution because he was the first  
one to talk about the sexuality of women,'' said Ruth Lax, an 
author, psychologist and analyst who teaches at Cornell Medical 
School. ``He didn't fully understand it, but he acknowledged it. 
That was a great step forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of Freud's work was not about women, however, but about  
people in general. 
</P>
<P>
	Throughout his life he revisited his theories, discarding,  
changing and trying out new ones. Like the patients he treated -- 
like the patients who today seek help from psychotherapists and 
analysts -- Freud was shaped by who he was, when and where he lived. 
</P>
<P>
	As his granddaughter Sophie Freud, a psychologist, has said of  
his theories: ``They should never be cast in cement; only religion 
does that. His work is a mixture of amazing leaps into the future, 
with other parts embedded in his own time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His ideas have provided a bedrock from which more modern theory  
has evolved, even though many were only grasped on a ``superficial 
... cocktail-party level,'' Gay said. 
</P>
<P>
	Freud offered explanations for the everyday mysteries. For  
example, sibling rivalry. ``Everybody has known brothers and 
sisters don't always get along,'' Gay said. ``But he gives you ways 
of understanding how this might come about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said Gay, ``Maybe one of the most important things he talks  
about is that people love and hate each other at the same time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Freud visited the United States just once. In September 1909 he  
spent a week at Clark University in Worcester, Mass., lecturing on 
psychoanalysis. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet it was this country that gave Freud's ideas their warmest  
embrace. 
</P>
<P>
	Why? Perhaps it's American insecurity, identity issues in a  
nation of immigrants, people always reinventing themselves; or, in 
a culture that exalts the striver, another way to seek personal and 
interpersonal perfection. 
</P>
<P>
	Freud, if he were alive today, might not recognize his legacy,  
much less approve. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet a direct lineage can be traced from the neurotic Europeans  
on Freud's couch -- really more of a chaise lounge draped with an 
oriental rug -- to today's walking wounded of America talking 
upright to psychotherapists about anything from childhood abuse to 
marriage troubles and alcoholism to neurotic pets. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, it's normal in much of the world to seek professional  
help for what ails the mind. 
</P>
<P>
	In Japan, psychologist Rika Kayama writes a magazine advice  
column and appears on TV variety and quiz shows. 
</P>
<P>
	In Scotland, two policewomen sent to the 1996 school massacre in  
the town of Dunblane, where 16 children and a teacher died, are 
suing their employers, claiming they didn't get enough counseling 
for stress. 
</P>
<P>
	Few people in India can afford psychotherapy, but they can call  
and seek advice from Dr. Broota, a popular voice on New Delhi 
radio. 
</P>
<P>
	In Russia, where Freud's works were once banned and dissidents  
were tossed into psychiatric wards as punishment, people now clamor 
for therapy to cure stress, sex problems, alcoholism, drug abuse. 
</P>
<P>
	Similarly, the Chinese used to denounce psychology as bourgeois  
and told the insane to improve their thinking by reading Mao 
Tse-tung. These days they worry about a therapist shortage. Many 
cities now offer counseling hotlines; Shanghai has at least nine. 
</P>
<P>
	Buenos Aires claims the world's highest per capita supply of  
psychoanalysts, many clustered in one part of town. It's called 
``Villa Freud.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
