<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 16:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brickyard Finish Goes Up in Smoke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Dale Jarrett drove 'round and 'round in the  
Brickyard 400 today, with a phalanx of drivers chasing him. It 
promised to be a quite a finish. 
</P>
<P>
	Then it all went up in a puff of smoke.  
</P>
<P>
	When Dave Marcis' engine went ``poof'' on lap 142, so did all  
the questions about who would make it to the end of the race and 
who wouldn't. Given a chance to stop for gas and tires, everyone 
made it fine -- except none of them even came close to catching 
Jarrett. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anything was possible,'' said Jeff Gordon, who was right in  
the mix of leaders and knew he wasn't going to make it to the 
checkered flag without stopping once more for gas. ``But it doesn't 
matter, because the caution did come out and that's the way that it 
ended.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of nervously watching a shootout at the end, the  
leaders' pit crews had to hustle into action. Jarrett gambled and 
took two tires, then easily drove away to his second Brickyard 
victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``The caution came out, and I said, `Here we go again. What do  
we do?''' said Jarrett, the Winston Cup points leader who ran out 
of gas last year at the Brickyard. ``Do we get four tires? I said 
two, and Todd agreed with that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's Todd, as in Parrott, Jarrett's crew chief. He's the one  
who told Jarrett with about 40 laps to go that he could make it to 
the end without refueling. 
</P>
<P>
	A few laps later, car owner Robert Yates was asked the same  
question. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes,'' Yates said nervously, then pausing for a beat before  
rephrasing. ``Maybe. If we're lucky.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But if anyone on Jarrett's No. 88 Ford Taurus team was nervous,  
they didn't convey that to the man who was at the controls. 
</P>
<P>
	When Jarrett, Mark Martin, Bobby Labonte and Gordon emerged from  
their final pit stops, only Gordon had a car as fast as Jarrett's. 
All the leaders took two fresh tires except Gordon, who took four 
and made up several spots to finish third. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just didn't have enough laps to get it done,'' Gordon said.  
</P>
<P>
	Jarrett's car was so strong that it didn't matter that he only  
had two new tires. 
</P>
<P>
	``With two tires, we had no idea what it would do,'' Jarrett  
said. ``We hadn't tried it. ... Once we got out front, it just took 
off. They were some of the fastest laps we ran all day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Burton also was in the mix for the final round of stops,  
shooting through the field like a rocket to make up several spots 
and take third. 
</P>
<P>
	But he decided to ignore crew chief Frank Stoddard, who called  
for four new tires. As the crew started removing the lug nuts on 
the driver's side, Burton drove away -- possibly leaving some of the 
lugs loose. He faded badly and finished fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	``There wasn't any miscommunication,'' Burton said. ``That was  
simply a case of the driver overruling the crew chief. I know it 
scared Frank, but taking two tires was the only thing we could 
do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the smoke cleared, the 320,000 fans who packed the stands  
for the sixth Brickyard got to see some intriguing pit strategy. 
They'll have to wait at least until next year for a fantastic 
finish. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's just the way it is,'' Labonte said. ``Sometimes, the  
difference between first and second is that piece of paper.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not this time.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
