<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Anheuser-Busch Teamsters Ratify Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Teamsters at all 12 of Anheuser-Busch Inc.'s  
plants across the country approved a five-year contract Saturday, 
but labor woes at the nation's largest brewery are not over. 
</P>
<P>
	Because union members at six breweries rejected local contract  
supplements, it was unclear whether the national contract would be 
accepted. 
</P>
<P>
	Anheuser-Busch -- maker of Budweiser, Bud Light, Michelob and  
other beers -- has said that until there is agreement on all 
national and local contracts there is no agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 8,000 bottlers, distillers, truck drivers and mechanics at  
the domestic breweries ratified the national contract by a 59 
percent margin, Teamsters President James P. Hoffa said. 
</P>
<P>
	John E. Jacob, spokesman for Anheuser-Busch, said the two  
parties will likely talk about whether there is a middle ground. He 
said options could include establishing the national contract only 
in those breweries where local agreements were reached. 
</P>
<P>
	Local contract supplements were rejected in St. Louis;  
Cartersville, Ga.; Fort Collins, Colo.; and Jacksonville, Fla. Some 
locals at plants in Newark, N.J., and Los Angeles rejected the 
contract supplements, while others approved them. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
