<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 17:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Gives Gore Campaign Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore may be concerned  
about being perceived as too close to a president who was 
impeached, but that is not stopping him from using Bill Clinton's 
fund-raising prowess to boost his White House hopes. 
</P>
<P>
	The president extolled Gore's accomplishments Saturday during an  
outreach meeting with religious leaders here, calling Gore ``by far 
the most influential and effective and productive vice president'' 
in history and directly urging them to support him. 
</P>
<P>
	``An election is a job interview. He wants you to hire him,''  
Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do, I do,'' Gore interjected amid peals of laughter.  
</P>
<P>
	``And all of these other people that are running are perfectly  
nice people, but all of them are saying, 'Hire us too, we want to 
be president, and sooner or later we'll get around to telling you 
why,''' Clinton continued. ``You already know more about him than 
anybody else running.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later, the president addressed a fund-raiser for the Gore 2000  
presidential campaign committee, the first of a series of such 
events featuring Clinton. The president also will attend four 
fund-raisers in the nation's capital, two next week and two on 
Sept. 22. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's dinner at the State House Convention Center was  
expected to draw 500 of Arkansas' most influential Democrats, with 
each asked to contribute at least $500. Other scheduled speakers 
included Sen. Blanche Lincoln, D-Ark.; U.S. Transportation 
Secretary Rodney Slater and Arkansas Attorney General Mark Pryor. 
</P>
<P>
	Privately, Gore has told associates he had felt the drag of  
Clinton's impeachment on attempts to get his own campaign in gear 
during the first half of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore campaign officials said last week they were confident the  
public was well past any unease about Clinton and his personal 
behavior. But it was clear Saturday that public pairings of Clinton 
and Gore were planned carefully planned so the politicians would 
not come across as a team. 
</P>
<P>
	The vice president arrived in Little Rock separately from  
Clinton, flying in from Chicago where he was speaking to a meeting 
of the Rainbow Coalition. Clinton and Gore were appearing together 
for a private meeting with farmers and African-American ministers 
before the fund-raising dinner. 
</P>
<P>
	They met with about 75 farmers at a coffee house near the  
Arkansas River, shedding their blue jackets while they chatted with 
the casually dressed farmers about an array of problems, including 
subsidized rice from Japan and subsidized cotton from China. Both 
crops are grown in Arkansas. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore proclaimed the current farm bill ``badly broken'' and  
Clinton said he would try to keep Congress in session all year if 
necessary to fix it. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's campaign has stressed that the president plays no  
hands-on role in stump strategy -- even as the campaign takes 
advantage of Clinton's ability to invigorate Democrats in the face 
of a primary challenge from Sen. Bill Bradley, and the possibility 
of a tough race against the Republican front-runner, Texas Gov. 
George W. Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Clinton strategist Paul Begala, who is supporting Gore  
from the sidelines, said Gore only stands to benefit from having 
Clinton in his corner, in terms of fund raising and putting the 
full force of presidential power behind Gore's policy ideas. 
</P>
<P>
	``This slavish devotion to Bush's lead in the polls is breeding  
a surrenderist strategy among a few faint-hearted Democrats,'' 
Begala said. ``I don't think people are going to say, 'Clinton 
cheated on his wife, so let's go back to Reaganomics and give more 
tax cuts to the rich.' And that's exactly what the other side, the 
Republicans would do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Gore and Clinton were teaming up again on the campaign  
trail, the Bradley team watched from the sidelines with little 
noticeable interest. 
</P>
<P>
	``All presidential elections are about the future and people are  
going to make a judgment of who they want for the future, not so 
much a calculation about the past,'' said Bradley spokesman Eric 
Hauser. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990807.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 17:10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tenn. Titans Explore New Stadium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The Tennessee Titans, anxious to check  
out their new stadium, held a dress rehearsal today at Adelphia 
Coliseum. And the initial reviews are just what the team wanted to 
hear. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's awesome,'' said Tony Wakefield of Nashville, who showed  
up with his 19-year-old son Jeremiah. ``I've been driving by the 
stadium for months. My wife is sick of me driving by this place. 
We're just about to bust.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More than 49,000 owners of personal seat licenses, who have the  
right to buy season tickets, were invited to watch the team end its 
first week of training camp with a practice and rookie scrimmage. 
</P>
<P>
	The Titans play their first exhibition game at the stadium Aug.  
27 against the Atlanta Falcons with the season opener Sept. 12 
against Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, 41,637 PSL owners showed up for their first chance  
to sit in their seats and check out what the $292 million stadium 
looks like with players on the field. It didn't hurt that the 
Titans eased the 90-degree plus heat with cut-rate concessions. 
</P>
<P>
	The players also had the opportunity for a sneak peek of game  
days by driving themselves to the stadium before fanning out to 
meet fans and sign autographs. 
</P>
<P>
	``How nice it is to finally have a home,' said free safety  
Marcus Robertson. ``It's real exciting. At the same time, it's 
going to be kind of overwhelming when we get to that first 
preseason game. The guys are real excited with the buzz.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Jeff Fisher thanked the crowd, which was larger than the  
team could fit into Vanderbilt Stadium where Tennessee played last 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been four years Aug. 11 when this whole thing started,''  
Fisher said of the move from Houston. ``This is the start of a new 
era.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the 67,700-seat stadium, which sits next to Interstates 24  
and 65 and across the Cumberland River from downtown Nashville, 
drew the biggest raves. 
</P>
<P>
	The team played one year in Memphis and last season at  
Vanderbilt Stadium in Nashville. 
</P>
<P>
	Television sets still have to be installed near concession  
areas, and the stairwells need sweeping. 
</P>
<P>
	But Joe and Cindy Holland of Nashville said maybe critics will  
stop complaining and start attending games now that the team is no 
longer playing in college stadiums. 
</P>
<P>
	The franchise drew a league-worst average of 28,095 playing the  
1997 season in Memphis' Liberty Bowl and 37,444 last year at 
Vanderbilt Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hollands, who have attended NFL games at Chicago's Soldier  
Field, Atlanta's Georgia Dome and Minnesota's Metrodome, have been 
waiting for the Titans' new stadium to open to have the NFL 
experience in Nashville. 
</P>
<P>
	``Vandy did not compare,'' Mrs. Holland said. ``I hated  
Vanderbilt.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
