<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Hopefuls Take Shots at Bush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- Republicans from Steve Forbes to Gary Bauer  
took aim Saturday at an absent Texas Gov. George W. Bush, while the 
GOP front-runner and other big names in the presidential field 
skipped a meeting of Midwestern activists. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander proposed a ``12th  
commandment'' to go along with the one about Republicans not 
attacking each other. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need a 12th Commandment for Republicans,'' Alexander said:  
``When picking a president, thou shalt have a contest, and the 
contest shall be on the issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Conservative activist Bauer warned that leading Republicans are  
cheating the party by not debating the GOP's direction. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we're not willing to confront each other on the direction  
of the party, how are we going to confront Al Gore?'' Bauer asked. 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer, Alexander, Forbes and commentator Alan Keyes were among a  
shrunken list of Republican contenders who spoke at a meeting of 
GOP activists from 13 Midwestern states. 
</P>
<P>
	Commentator Pat Buchanan dropped out Friday, and former Vice  
President Dan Quayle sent word earlier Saturday he wouldn't show 
up. Aides said later it was because Quayle's mother is ill. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush and former Cabinet officer Elizabeth Dole never agreed to  
attend the meeting. Thus the 850 delegates found themselves with 
the lesser-known candidates focusing harsh words on Bush, enjoying 
a huge lead in the early polls and in raising money. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesman Eric Woolson said Bush was spending the weekend on  
vacation with his family in Maine. ``This is the last weekend 
before his daughters start back to school,'' said Woolson. ``He 
wanted to be with them. He understands the event in Omaha is 
important, but his commitment to his daughters is his first 
priority.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Ultimately you're not going to win by being anointed by the  
elite in Washington,'' Forbes said. ``Ultimately, the people make 
the decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I do think that we face a crisis in this country, a crisis of  
arrogance,'' Keyes said. ``A crisis of those who believe that they 
are going to usurp the votes of our people, substituting money 
power and media power for the actual decisions that people make in 
the voting booth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Keyes argued that Bush' skipping many early campaign events  
amounts to a ``spit in the face of ordinary voters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's big lead in the polls drew scorn from candidates who  
insisted that voters haven't really begun to focus on the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``Strong message, ground forces and resources: Ultimately that's  
how you win,'' Forbes said. ``When the American people start to 
focus nationally on this campaign later this year and the next 
year, we are going to be ready. Others, I think, are going to be 
following in our wake.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the conference was opened by Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, who  
dropped out of the campaign last month, endorsed Bush and told 
reporters Saturday his nomination is inevitable. 
</P>
<P>
	``The stars are aligned,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Alexander rejected that argument, saying Bush will inevitably  
have to engage other contenders. 
</P>
<P>
	``Republicans are looking for a winner and a leader, and we  
don't get that by letting big money or big media decide this for 
us,'' Alexander said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer said many in the GOP see Bush leading the party away from  
its conservative base. ``There's a lot of discontent in the 
Republican ranks,'' Bauer said. ``There are people who are yearning 
for a Reagan-type message.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said many activists are becoming annoyed that Bush is  
skipping events. ``I would hope the time is fast approaching when 
it is getting to be more than disappointment,'' Bauer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Delegates were treated to a list of GOP congressional leaders  
who were beginning the job of selling a tax-cut package they've 
approved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
