<DOCNO> APW19990807.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 12:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Government Padlocks Nevada Brothel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MUSTANG, Nev. (AP) -- When the government burned down Joe  
Conforte's bordello, he just bought another one. When the IRS 
seized that one for taxes and auctioned it, Conforte bought back 
the $5 million-a-year operation on the sly. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, with Conforte on the lam and the payoffs that helped keep  
it open dried up, the Mustang Ranch is on the verge of being 
padlocked. For good. 
</P>
<P>
	The bordello's court-ordered closure Monday will end a colorful  
chapter in Nevada history -- while cutting $230,000 from tiny Storey 
County's budget and throwing about 70 legal prostitutes out of 
work. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a sad situation because you're going to have prostitutes  
on the streets in Reno like you do in Las Vegas,'' former Mustang 
manager and county Commissioner Shirley Colletti said. Prostitution 
is legal in Storey County but illegal in Reno and surrounding 
Washoe County. 
</P>
<P>
	The story of the Mustang Ranch is the story of Conforte, a  
squat, cigar-puffing, raspy-voiced Sicilian immigrant who landed in 
Oakland, Calif., in 1950, and supplemented his cab driver's income 
by pointing men to prostitutes. 
</P>
<P>
	He opened his own brothels in Northern California before moving  
to less fussy Nevada. There, he teamed up with veteran madam Jesse 
Sally Burgess to operate the Triangle Ranch near Wadsworth, 30 
miles east of Reno. 
</P>
<P>
	When Washoe County District Attorney Bill Raggio tried to close  
the place down, Conforte moved it just outside the county. Their 
battle led to a feeble extortion plot in 1959 in which Conforte 
accused Raggio of plying a woman under 18 with liquor in a 
seduction attempt. Conforte didn't know Raggio was taping the 
conversation, which sent him to jail for extortion. 
</P>
<P>
	While Conforte was in prison, a judge declared the Triangle  
Ranch a public nuisance and it was burned down in 1960. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, Conforte and Burgess bought the nearby Mustang Ranch,  
where a buzzer let visitors through a gate in a 10-foot fence and 
also signaled the prostitutes to line up in the red-wallpapered 
lobby for pairing off. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal government kept the heat on Conforte's tendency to  
overlook paying taxes until he fled to Brazil in 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	Then he cut a deal with the U.S. government to testify that he  
bribed U.S. District Judge Harry Claiborne in an effort to stay out 
of prison. Claiborne was removed from the bench and imprisoned. 
Conforte was back at the Mustang after a year behind bars. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1990, he and Burgess declared bankruptcy and the IRS seized  
the Mustang Ranch and sold it at a tax auction. 
</P>
<P>
	A brother of Conforte's lawyer made the lone bid and snapped it  
up for $1.49 million -- a tenth of the back taxes. Conforte said he 
had no part in the bidding. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Storey County Commission met to consider whether to  
allow prostitution to resume at the 104-room brothel, Conforte, 
then listed only as the manager, made the issue moot. 
</P>
<P>
	``We reopened this morning,'' he announced. ``I'm not here to  
ask for a license. I'm here as a common courtesy to this board to 
tell you how it is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1991, with the federal government still after him for taxes,  
Conforte fled to South America again while remaining on retainer 
with the Mustang management as a $10,000-a-month consultant. 
</P>
<P>
	Testimony at a trial last month alleged that 10 times that  
amount was siphoned from the brothel to South America. 
</P>
<P>
	That trial also confirmed that Ms. Colletti was on the payroll  
as manager while serving as a county commissioner. A jury convicted 
her of conspiring with two shell companies to conceal Conforte as 
the true owner of the $5 million-a-year operation. 
</P>
<P>
	Following the conviction, U.S. District Court Judge Howard  
McKibben ordered the brothel closed at 5 p.m. Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	While other county officials have denied receiving tributes, the  
brothel has helped out in other ways. A school bus was bought for 
the county, there were almost unquestioned handouts to anybody 
asking for them, and reduced rent for the needy at a Mustang-owned 
trailer park. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have been a very good neighbor to us. They've donated  
thousands of dollars to the community,'' said county commission 
vice-chairman Carl Trink at a meeting to debate how to absorb the 
loss of revenue generated by the brothel. 
</P>
<P>
	Others who find the brothel morally offensive are just glad to  
see it go. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would like to see this historic day as the beginning of the  
end of the brothels in Nevada,'' said Barbara Jones, a member of 
the Sunrise Fellowship and Point of Grace in Reno. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
