<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Braves' Perez Begins Suspension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Braves catcher Eddie Perez withdrew his appeal of  
a four-game suspension and began serving the penalty Saturday, 
forcing Atlanta to recall Pascual Matos from Triple-A Richmond. 
</P>
<P>
	The Braves optioned first baseman Randall Simon to Richmond,  
where he will have to spend a minimum of 10 days. Since Atlanta 
carries only two catchers on its 25-man roster and a suspended 
player can't be replaced, Matos was needed as a backup to Greg 
Myers. 
</P>
<P>
	Perez was suspended and fined $1,000 for triggering a brawl in a  
game with the Philadelphia Phillies on July 30. He originally 
appealed the suspension, but decided it was futile to wait for a 
hearing in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``Better to do it now than later,'' Perez said prior to  
Saturday's game against the San Francisco Giants. ``I don't think 
I'm going to get any less than four games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the hearing would not have been held until the Braves  
visited New York the final week of the regular season for a 
three-game series against the Mets. Prior to Saturday's games, New 
York led the Braves by 1 1/2 games in the NL East. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people told me I might get one game less if I waited  
until we got to New York,'' Perez said. ``But I can't take a 
chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The brawl began after Phillies pitcher Paul Byrd hit Perez in  
the third inning, the second time in less than a week that Byrd hit 
his former teammate with a pitch. 
</P>
<P>
	The following inning, the pair exchanged words when Byrd came to  
the plate. Perez threw a punch, setting off the brawl. 
</P>
<P>
	Braves manager Bobby Cox drew a two-game suspension, which he  
served, for his actions in the same game. Cox returned to the field 
after being ejected in the previous inning for arguing a 
double-play call. 
</P>
<P>
	Perez, who will miss the final two games of the Giants' series  
and the first two games of a three-game series with the Houston 
Astros, said he doesn't hold a grudge against Byrd. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll be all right,'' Perez said. ``He's still my friend.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
