<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Possible Buyers Say No to Examiner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- With two potential buyers turning down the  
chance to buy the San Francisco Examiner, newspaper analysts, 
journalists and readers are predicting that the paper and its bold 
headlines and raucous style will become another casualty in an 
American institution: the afternoon newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	The paper's parent company, The Hearst Corp., announced Friday  
that it would buy the larger San Francisco Chronicle. The Chronicle 
reported the sale was for $660 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal, Hearst will buy the Chronicle and then put the  
Examiner up for sale. If Hearst can't find a buyer for its 
afternoon paper, it will combine them into a morning daily. 
</P>
<P>
	Speculation about the future is rampant in the Bay Area. Would a  
marriage of the restrained Chronicle and the scrappy Examiner be 
happy? Would the lost competition be offset by the increased 
resources of a unified paper? 
</P>
<P>
	``I would like to have the choice,'' said Frank Ingram, a sales  
representative who works in San Francisco. ``Every time we lose a 
paper, we lose another piece of our country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But others are optimistic that a richer newspaper would be  
better. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe for the first time in decades people will take San  
Francisco journalism seriously,'' said Examiner reporter Marsha 
Ginsberg. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics have long complained that the Chronicle is too staid and  
the Examiner too thin. The Chronicle is the 12th largest newspaper 
in the country, with 482,000 daily readers. The Examiner has 
115,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Executives from two local competitors, Knight Ridder and  
MediaNews Group, said they are not interested in buying. Knight 
Ridder owns the San Jose Mercury News and Contra Costa Newspapers 
group. MediaNews owns five smaller Bay Area newspapers. 
</P>
<P>
	``There simply isn't enough demand for the print medium to  
justify having two papers,'' said Charles Baird, an economist at 
California State University, Hayward. Long commutes, television 
news and declining mass transit have killed many afternoon papers. 
</P>
<P>
	History is not on the Examiner's side. Although most American  
cities once had several newspapers, only 47 still have two or more 
dailies. Afternoon papers from San Diego to Milwaukee to Pittsburgh 
have closed, although they still outnumber morning papers 781 to 
721. 
</P>
<P>
	As in several other two-paper cities, the Chronicle and Examiner  
share business operations to cut costs. During the past 15 years, 
similar arrangements have been terminated in 12 cities. Only once, 
in St. Louis, did the second paper get purchased. It lingered two 
years before folding. 
</P>
<P>
	Whatever the Examiner's fate, local journalists say they will  
miss the unflagging rivalry between the city's two venerable 
newspapers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like the Yankees selling to the Mets,'' said Carl Hall, a  
union leader and science writer for the Chronicle. ``I have a hard 
time thinking of myself as a Met. But at least we're not out on the 
street.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
