<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wright Headed to Clippers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Lorenzen Wright, the center-forward from the Los  
Angeles Clippers who was contemplating a job with the Lakers, 
instead will be traded to the Atlanta Hawks on Sunday for two No. 1 
picks, The Associated Press learned Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Two NBA sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, confirmed  
the trade. Atlanta will give up its own No. 1 pick and one 
originally belonging to Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright, who turned down a $30 million, six-year offer to stay  
with the Clippers, should get similar money from the Hawks. Atlanta 
is over the salary cap, but has a trade exception worth $4.4 
million that it can use in this deal. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the 6-foot-11 Wright was reportedly contemplating a  
one-year, $2 million offer from the Lakers, which came as shocking 
news to the Pacers and Hawks -- both of who were trying to get 
Wright in a sign-and-trade deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hawks and Clippers had discussed a Jim Jackson-for-Wright  
deal early last week, but Atlanta decided against it. 
</P>
<P>
	But when given a chance to get the three-year veteran for the  
price of two draft picks, the Hawks decided to do it. Atlanta had 
four No. 1 picks this year and kept three of the players -- guard 
Jason Terry, center-forward Cal Bowlder and guard Dion Glover. 
</P>
<P>
	With the fourth pick, the Hawks drafted forward Jumaine Jones  
but immediately traded his rights to Philadelphia for a future No. 
1 that initially belonged to Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	That pick will be sent to the Clippers along with the Hawks' top  
selection in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta called a news conference for Sunday morning, but a team  
spokesman would not reveal the announcement. A Clippers spokesman 
could not be reached. 
</P>
<P>
	The addition of Wright gives the Hawks some depth and security  
along the front line. Alan Henderson, last season's starting power 
forward, missed the playoffs with an eye injury that has been slow 
to heal. His backup, Grant Long, is a free agent. 
</P>
<P>
	After being swept in the second round of the playoffs by the  
Knicks, Atlanta has been one of the busiest teams during the 
offseason. The Hawks traded their starting backcourt, sending point 
guard Mookie Blaylock to Golden State for the pick that landed 
Terry, and Steve Smith, their leading scorer four years in a row, 
to the Portland Trail Blazers for Isaiah Rider and Jackson. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clippers have already lost free agents Rodney Rogers and  
Darrick Martin without getting anything in return, although they 
did pull off a sign-and-trade deal with Cleveland in which they 
received Derek Anderson and Johnny Newman in exchange for Lamond 
Murray. 
</P>
<P>
	Los Angeles did manage to re-sign shooting guard Eric  
Piatkowski, but Sherman Douglas and Tyrone Nesby remain free 
agents. The Clippers have the right to match any offer made to 
Nesby. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright averaged 6.6 points and 7.5 rebounds last season,  
splitting time at center with rookie Michael Olowokandi and at 
forward with Maurice Taylor. 
</P>
<P>
	The 23-year-old made it clear to the Clippers that he did not  
want to continue playing for them. 
</P>
<P>
	The draft pick that originally belonged to Toronto is lottery  
protected, meaning the Raptors will keep it unless they make the 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Toronto first traded the pick to the Knicks for John Wallace,  
and New York sent it to Philadelphia for Mirsad Turkcan. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990807.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 02:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NASCAR Tries To Take Over Brickyard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The roar of engines can be heard several  
blocks away from Indianapolis Motor Speedway. It's not the 
high-pitched wail that penetrates the neighborhood in May, but a 
deep, raspy whine that carries a message of change. 
</P>
<P>
	From Indiana's favorite racing sons to the folks who live a  
stone's throw from the speedway, the old Brickyard is rounding up 
stock-car converts at an astounding rate. It's summertime, which 
means Indy becomes NASCAR country. 
</P>
<P>
	Five years after the good ol' boys first fired up their noisy  
engines here in 1994, the Brickyard 400 has done more than find a 
niche in the Camelot of racing. These guys look like they're taking 
over the place. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody wants to be where the action is, and the biggest  
action is in NASCAR,'' said John Andretti, whose family name has 
been synonymous with Indianapolis for decades. ``That's probably 
the biggest reason why you see us come down here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Brickyard 400 is still second to the Daytona 500 on NASCAR's  
list of prestige and winnings; the purse for Saturday's race will 
be $6.1 million, compared with $7.3 million at Daytona earlier this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	But the race attracts so many fans, merchandise sales and  
interest that it is making a strong bid to unseat the Indy 500 as 
the biggest race in Indianapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	``How can you guys have any doubt in your mind that this is the  
biggest race in our minds right now?'' asked Tony Stewart, another 
Indiana native who has fled the fractured world of American 
open-wheel racing for the riches and recognition of NASCAR's 
Winston Cup series. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know ever since I was born, I can remember coming to the  
Speedway,'' Stewart said. ``And you always dreamed that someday you 
could be the first one to the checkered flag here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like Stewart and Andretti, Jeff Gordon and Kenny Irwin dreamed  
about racing at Indy during the time they spent in Indiana. All of 
them are here in gaudy stock cars instead of the sleek open-wheel 
machines they were trained to drive as they rose through Indiana's 
racing ranks. 
</P>
<P>
	And they understand the explosiveness of the issue concerning  
who rules the Brickyard after American open-wheel racing split into 
two divisions -- CART and the Indy Racing League. 
</P>
<P>
	All but the outspoken Andretti were silent when asked about how  
Indy and racing have changed since NASCAR showed up here in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nope,'' Gordon said with a smile when asked if he'd like to  
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The media and race fans around here are not nearly as guarded.  
</P>
<P>
	``NASCAR's more fan friendly,'' said Lisa Scott, sitting on her  
sister's lawn across the street from the speedway. ``The 500, 
they've just become too big for their britches, if you ask me. They 
cater to the richest people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Joyce Scott, who has lived on 28th Street, in sight of the  
speedway for 16 years, said, ``I'd rather go to the Brickyard than 
the 500.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stock car racing gets strong TV ratings in Indy, too. The  
Indianapolis market was third in ratings for the 1999 Daytona 500 
and first for Winston Cup's Atlanta race. It was first for the last 
two Brickyard 400s, and consistently pulls top-five ratings for 
Winston Cup races. 
</P>
<P>
	NASCAR memorabilia sales, known for their relentless strength,  
have taken over the streets around the speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you see Dale Earnhardt bring in eight transporters with  
his clothing and memorabilia, that's pretty big,'' said Fred 
Nation, the speedway's vice president for corporate communications. 
</P>
<P>
	All this led the Indianapolis Star to proclaim this week that  
the Brickyard 400 ``has shoved the Indianapolis 500 into secondary 
status.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nation disputes this, pointing out that the Indy 500 still draws  
a bigger crowd, better local TV ratings and far more international 
interest than the Brickyard. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Indy 500 is an event that lasts more than two weeks,''  
Nation said. ``The Brickyard 400 is a three-day event.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the extent of NASCAR's success in the heartland was never  
more evident than on Friday morning, when the four Winston Cup 
drivers with Indiana ties gathered in one room to trade quips and 
stories. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd say even winning a go-cart race here would be the biggest  
thing,'' said Irwin, a Winston Cup rookie and Indianapolis native. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked to name their favorite Indiana tracks and race cars, none  
of the drivers came up with what used to be the obvious answer -- 
Indy-cars at Indy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Stock car, Indianapolis,'' Gordon said. ``I thought that was  
an easy question.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990807.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 18:56:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Saints Already Nursing Wounds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LA CROSSE, Wis. (AP) -- New Orleans Saints coach Mike Ditka went  
into training camp saying he wanted his team to be tough and 
hard-hitting with a nasty attitude. He was referring to the games, 
though, not the practice field. 
</P>
<P>
	With their first exhibition game still almost a week away, the  
Saints on Saturday were already nursing wounds inflicted by another 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	Wide receiver Keith Poole's nose was broken, his left eye was  
purple and swollen closed. It took six stitches to close cuts above 
and below it, inflicted Friday during a melee that culminated a day 
of brawls in two practice sessions with the Kansas City Chiefs. 
</P>
<P>
	Poole said, and television footage appeared to confirm, that  
Chiefs free safety Jerome Woods hit him late. When Poole turned to 
confront Woods, Kansas City cornerback Chris Dishman grabbed Poole, 
pinned his arms back and stripped off Poole's helmet. A moment 
later, Chiefs cornerback Carlton Gray dove over Poole's back and 
hit him in the eye. 
</P>
<P>
	Coaches separated the players and called off the rest of  
practice, but as the teams left the field, Poole challenged Gray, 
nearly touching off another brawl. 
</P>
<P>
	``I shouldn't have done it,'' Poole said Saturday. ``But it was  
a cheap shot and the guy knows it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The scrimmage planned for Saturday morning was canceled.  
</P>
<P>
	Friday night, additional police were dispatched to the cafeteria  
where the teams ate dinner before the Saints returned to La Crosse. 
</P>
<P>
	Although there were no serious injuries from the fights, Ditka  
implied that Chiefs coaches encouraged their players to 
deliberately hurt people and his players had to fight back. 
</P>
<P>
	``Are you going to tell your guys, `Just take what they give  
you. Let them hit you in the back, take their helmets off and swing 
them at you.''' Ditka said. ``That's bull. 
</P>
<P>
	``They tried to hit our top running back (Ricky Williams), when  
the play is over, and to have one of their coaches say, ``Take him 
out,' from what I understand. I don't know if I can say that for 
sure, but I heard that. That bothers me. Then again, I guess you 
consider the source.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ditka said one of his coaches told him the Chief's coaches were  
telling their players to take Williams out. 
</P>
<P>
	Offensive lineman Kyle Turley also said it was a hit on Williams  
that set off the chain of events. 
</P>
<P>
	``They took a couple of cheap shots at Ricky, and that's not  
right,'' Turley said. ``No. 97 (Ty Parten) had some cheap shots on 
Ricky, he tackled him when he was in the middle of a pile. We 
started making plays on them, and they started taking people out. 
We were just defending ourselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chiefs general manager Carl Peterson said no one was to blame,  
but Saints defensive line coach Walt Corey said Chiefs first-year 
coach Gunther Cunningham failed to control his team after fights 
erupted throughout the morning session. 
</P>
<P>
	``The person in charge over there is to blame,'' Corey said,  
indicating the Chiefs. ``Whoever's in charge is in total control. 
It was supposed to be a practice, not a fight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cunningham apparently tried to stop the fights. He loudly  
scolded his team after Kansas City tackle Marcus Spears used his 
helmet to hit Saints defensive end Brady Smith in the back of the 
head during one brawl. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told the players that we weren't going to play like this and  
it just kept escalating,'' said Cunningham, who sent Spears to the 
locker room after the incident. ``I tried to calm them down and we 
said if it didn't we were going to stop practice. I looked at Mike 
and he said he felt the same way, so we stopped.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Spears later apologized for his actions.  
</P>
<P>
	``I apologize to this organization and the team because you  
can't have that,'' he said. ``In the heat of battle, things are 
going on. But you've got to keep your composure and I lost my 
composure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ditka said he had not heard from the league and did not know if  
there would be any sanctions or investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our guys stuck together,'' Ditka said. ``I like that, and I  
can't stand up and be too critical of that, and I'm not going to be 
critical of them. What we did, we did in defense. I didn't think we 
precipitated any of it. That makes a difference. ... We were the 
guys that just reciprocated. Maybe we shouldn't have done that but 
we did. We fought back.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990807.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 18:56:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Saints Already Nursing Wounds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LA CROSSE, Wis. (AP) -- New Orleans Saints coach Mike Ditka went  
into training camp saying he wanted his team to be tough and 
hard-hitting with a nasty attitude. He was referring to the games, 
though, not the practice field. 
</P>
<P>
	With their first exhibition game still almost a week away, the  
Saints on Saturday were already nursing wounds inflicted by another 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	Wide receiver Keith Poole's nose was broken, his left eye was  
purple and swollen closed. It took six stitches to close cuts above 
and below it, inflicted Friday during a melee that culminated a day 
of brawls in two practice sessions with the Kansas City Chiefs. 
</P>
<P>
	Poole said, and television footage appeared to confirm, that  
