<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ocean Marathon Winner Sets Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) -- David Meca-Medina, the second-ranked  
swimmer in the world, won Saturday's Ocean Marathon with more than 
five minutes to spare, eclipsing the course record by six seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Meca-Medina, of Spain, was a favorite to win the 22-mile race  
around Absecon Island along with top-ranked Stephane Lecat, who 
dropped out about three hours into the trip. Meca-Medina finished 
in six hours, 56 minutes and 43 seconds to win the $4,200 purse. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany's Andre Wilde, was second after finishing in 7:02.17.  
Slovenian Igor Majcen, who completed the course in 7:07.26 seconds, 
was third. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 25 swimmers who began Saturday morning -- 12 women and 13  
men -- only 21 finished. Three of the four dropouts were men, 
including sixth-ranked Christof Wandratch of Germany, who said he'd 
failed to train enough. 
</P>
<P>
	``You could get seasick. You could take a bad gulp of salt  
water. You could get a jellyfish sting,'' said race spokeswoman 
Lauralee Dobbins. ``People have dropped out because of hypothermia 
and sometimes they get beaten up by the tides.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dobbins said seas were calm Saturday morning, speeding the  
beginning of the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``They didn't really meet any ferocious tides or currents until  
the last hour,'' she added. 
</P>
<P>
	First-time racer Gabe Lindsay, of Oviedo, Fla., took fourth  
place. 
</P>
<P>
	``This guy went out like a madman, way ahead of all the pros,''  
said race director Sid Cassidy. ``He absolutely astounded me.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
