<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pro Football Hall of Fame Capsules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CANTON, Ohio (AP) -- Sketches of those elected to the Pro  
Football Hall of Fame: 
</P>
<P>
                          *Eric Dickerson    	
</P>
<P>
                           *Running Back    	
</P>
<P>
 *L.A. Rams (1983-87), Indianapolis Colts (1987-91), L.A. Raiders 	
</P>
<P>
                       (1992), Atlanta (1993) 	
</P>
<P>
	Ran for an NFL-record 2,105 yards with the Rams in 1984. He  
stands third on the career rushing list with 13,259 yards, having 
rushed for more than 1,000 yards seven times. Was the No. 1 pick by 
the Rams and second player overall in 1983. Named NFL Player of the 
Year in 1984 and the NFL Offensive Player of the Year in 1986. 
Gained a playoff-record 248 yards rushing in 1985 divisional 
playoff game. In 1987, was traded to Indianapolis in a blockbuster 
deal that also involved the Buffalo Bills. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Tom Mack    	
</P>
<P>
                              *Guard    	
</P>
<P>
                     *Los Angeles Rams (1966-78)    	
</P>
<P>
	Although he never made it to a Super Bowl, Mack was a frequent  
postseason player. He was selected to play in Pro Bowls 11 times in 
13 years. One reason was his durability; he never missed a game 
because of injury. The No. 1 pick by the Rams in 1966 played in 184 
straight games. 
</P>
<P>
                           *Ozzie Newsome    	
</P>
<P>
                             *Tight end    	
</P>
<P>
                     *Cleveland Browns (1978-90)    	
</P>
<P>
	Tops all NFL tight ends in career receptions. ``The Wizard of  
Oz'' went 150 games with at least one reception and totaled 662 
catches for 7,980 yards and 47 touchdowns in his 13 seasons. A 
first-round pick out of Alabama, he had 89 catches in 1983 and 
again in 1984. Caught 50 or more passes six seasons. Did not fumble 
in last 557 carries. Had three or more receptions in 112 games. 
Played in three AFC Championship game and was a Pro Bowl choice in 
1982, 1985 and 1986. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Bill Shaw    	
</P>
<P>
                              *Guard    	
</P>
<P>
                     *Buffalo Bills (1961-1969)    	
</P>
<P>
	The driving force of the Bills' offensive unit that emphasized  
the run. Was proficient in pass and run blocking. Named first-team 
All-AFL 1962-66. Selected to play in eight AFL All-Star games. 
Named to pro football's All-Decade Team of the 1960s and All-Time 
AFL Team. The captain for eight seasons, played on the Bills' 
championship teams of 1964 and 1965. 
</P>
<P>
                          *Lawrence Taylor    	
</P>
<P>
                            *Linebacker    	
</P>
<P>
                     *New York Giants (1981-1993)    	
</P>
<P>
	A quick and athletic linebacker who redefined his position.  
Anchored the Giants' defense in two Super Bowls wins (1987 and 
1991). Named NFL Most Valuable Player in 1986 following a season in 
which he record a career-high 20.5 sacks. Was the NFL Defensive 
Player of the Year in 1981, 1982 and 1986. Selected to 10 Pro 
Bowls. Recorded 132.5 sacks, which doesn't include the 9.5 sacks in 
1981 when the statistic wasn't official. Was selected to the 75th 
Anniversary All-Time Team. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990807.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 08:00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Some New Nursing Home Guidelines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Efforts to improve the nation's nursing homes include orders  
from President Clinton, suggestions from federal auditors and 
legislation in Congress: 

</P>
<P>
	On Clinton's order, the Department of Health and Human Services  
now: 
</P>
<P>
	-- Levies immediate fines of up to $10,000 for problem nursing  
homes, instead of giving them time to correct problems before 
facing penalties. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Requires state inspection agencies to respond more quickly --  
within 10 days -- to complaints alleging harm to residents. 

</P>
<P>
	New requirements proposed after the General Accounting Office,  
Congress' investigative arm, found evidence in two studies that at 
least one out of four homes provided such poor care that residents 
were harmed: 
</P>
<P>
	-- Inspections of nursing homes on nights and weekends so  
surveyors get a more complete picture of the care provided. 
</P>
<P>
	-- More thorough review of a home's efforts to fix problems.  

</P>
<P>
	In Congress, lawmakers are still considering legislation that  
would create a national criminal background check for the nursing 
home industry to ensure that abusive aides and nurses previously 
convicted of violent crimes are not rehired. 

</P>
<P>
	Under review are changes that would:  
</P>
<P>
	-- Target nursing home chains with a poor record of meeting state  
standards, so that they will be inspected more frequently. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Cut off inspection funds to states that continually have a  
poor record of citing nursing homes for substandard care. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Collect information on patient care in a national automated  
data system, so that federal and state officials can identify 
problem facilities earlier. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990807.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 11:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> State Sen. Wife in Nude Photo Flap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The wife of a top state lawmaker has quit her  
job with the Pennsylvania Turnpike Commission after technicians 
found nude photos of her that had been shot in the turnpike 
headquarters, the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette reported Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Turnpike Executive Director John Durbin had suspended Deborah  
Eckert Jubelirer, 43, after officials learned that a nude photo of 
her was in the commission computer system, the paper reported. She 
resigned Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Her husband is Senate President Pro Tem Robert Jubelirer. He had  
no comment, said an aide, David Atkinson. Aides said Jubelirer knew 
nothing of the situation and that he and his wife have separated. 
</P>
<P>
	A commission technician, Kenneth R. Manherz, was accused of  
shooting the photos with a digital camera that belonged to the 
commission, the newspaper said. He was fired Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	At least one other female employee at the turnpike building in  
Highspire appeared in the photos, but no action was taken because 
her role was minor, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Jubelirer, who earned $65,539 a year, could not be located  
for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Turnpike officials refused to discuss personnel issues.  
</P>
<P>
	``We consider the case closed,'' said Bill Capone, deputy  
executive director in charge of the marketing department. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
