<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands Battle Nevada Wildfires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RENO, Nev. (AP) -- Rain and cooler weather helped conquer one big  
fire in western Nevada but 3,000 firefighters continued battling 
more than 100 brush fires that have burned an area nearly the size 
of Rhode Island and were threatening some homes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically, all across the northern part of the state is  
fires,'' JoLynn Worley, spokeswoman for the Bureau of Land 
Management, said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	At 611,000 acres and growing, the fires threatened ranches and  
homes near the Oregon border, and smoke intermittently forced the 
closure of Interstate 80 on Friday near Lovelock, Winnemucca, 
Battle Mountain and Elko. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, firefighters said Friday night they had fully  
contained one of the worst blazes, Idaho's Mule Butte fire that had 
burned more than 92,500 acres. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a fire in eastern Idaho was sparked by lightning  
Friday afternoon and burned about 4,000 acres before it was 
contained. 
</P>
<P>
	In northeast Nevada's Elko County, a fast-moving brush fire  
burned two unoccupied mobile homes and forced the evacuation of at 
least 20 people in Spring Creek. Flames came within a few feet of 
some homes in that densely populated subdivision 12 miles southeast 
of Elko along the Ruby Mountains. 
</P>
<P>
	Fires also burned within a mile of a housing subdivision in  
Battle Mountain. But only three outbuildings had been destroyed, 
with no homes damaged or injuries reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the fires were sparked by more than 8,000 lightning  
strikes as thunderstorms rolled across the state. They were burning 
sage brush and cheat grass across remote, uninhabited range, 
forcing hand crews to hike for long distances. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was pretty steep. We ran into rattlesnakes. It was pretty  
tough conditions,'' firefighter Stan Henrich said. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 200 firefighters were focusing their attention on the  
Skyline housing subdivision near Battle Mountain, where a series of 
fires has burned more than 70,000 acres about 200 miles east of 
Reno. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
