<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Aug. 7, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	S. Korea Child Fire Victims Mourned  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- A mass funeral was held today for the  
19 kindergarten children who died in a pre-dawn fire while at 
summer camp. In Seoul's sun-Olympic Park, 1,200 family members and 
government officials stood silently with bowed heads, stifling sobs 
with handkerchiefs. Marine guards played a funeral dirge. The June 
29 blaze gutted a three-story dormitory at the Sealand Youth 
Training Center in Hwasung County, 60 miles southeast of Seoul. 
Four adults also were killed. 

</P>
<P>
	Gunmen Seize Russian Villages  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- About 500 gunmen seized two villages today in the  
southern Russian republic of Dagestan near its border with 
breakaway Chechnya, news reports said. The militants crossed from 
Chechnya into Dagestan early today and occupied the villages of 
Ansalt and Rakhat, the ITAR-Tass news agency quoted Dagestan 
Interior Ministry officials as saying. Dagestani authorities said 
the gunmen appeared to be from the same group blamed for an attack 
on a neighboring region last week, the fundamentalist Wahhabi 
Islamic movement. No casualties were immediately reported. 

</P>
<P>
	Thousands Battle Nevada Wildfires  
</P>
<P>
	RENO, Nev. (AP) -- Three thousand firefighters continued battling  
more than 100 brush fires that have burned an area nearly the size 
of Rhode Island and were threatening some homes. At 611,000 acres 
and growing, the fires threatened ranches and homes near the Oregon 
border, and smoke intermittently forced the closure of Interstate 
80 yesterday near Lovelock, Winnemucca, Battle Mountain and Elko. 
Firefighters said last night they had fully contained one of the 
worst blazes, Idaho's Mule Butte fire that had burned more than 
92,500 acres. 

</P>
<P>
	Two More Chinese Dissidents Detained  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Two more members of a banned Chinese dissident  
group have been detained by police, a group that monitors dissident 
activity said today. Chen Wei and Ouyang Yi were taken away 
yesterday and early today, respectively, in Suining, a city in the 
western province of Sichuan, the Hong Kong-based Information Center 
of Human Rights and Democratic Movement in China said. Chen and 
Ouyang are members of the China Democracy Party, a group set up 
last year to challenge the Chinese Communist Party's monopoly on 
power. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Concerned Over Peackeeper Attacks  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO officials are worried over an  
increase of violence aimed at international peacekeepers in the 
alliance's force in Kosovo. The attacts are considered a threat to 
the ability of NATO and the United Nations to set up a civil 
administration in Kosovo to run the territory until elections can 
be held. Meanwhile, efforts are continuing to establish a strong 
international police force in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Turkish Union Leader Fatally Shot  
</P>
<P>
	ZONGULDAK, Turkey (AP) -- The deputy head of Turkey's largest  
labor union confederation was shot to death outside his home early 
today in the Black Sea coastal city of Zonguldak, the Anatolia news 
agency said. Semsi Denizer, 49, became popular when he led some 
50,000 striking coal miners on a 165-mile protest march from 
Zonguldak to the capital, Ankara, for higher pay in 1991. He was 
general-secretary of the Turk-Is labor confederation. The 
assailant, Cengiz Balik, who has a long criminal record, was 
arrested after the attack, police said. 

</P>
<P>
	Hearst Buys Rival S.F. Chronicle  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The San Francisco Chronicle was purchased  
yesterday by its century-old nemesis, the Hearst Corp., publisher 
of the San Francisco Examiner. Under the deal, which ends of one of 
the last great rivalries of American journalism, Hearst Corp. will 
buy the Chronicle and then put the Examiner up for sale. If Hearst 
can't find a buyer for its afternoon paper, it will combine them 
into a morning daily, an idea that was immediately condemned. 

</P>
<P>
	LT, Others Head Into Football Hall  
</P>
<P>
	CANTON, Ohio (AP) -- Former New York Giants linebacker Lawrence  
Taylor will be joined today by running back Eric Dickerson, 
offensive guards Tom Mack and Billy Shaw and tight end Ozzie 
Newsome for their induction into the Pro Football Hall of Fame. 
Taylor retired with two Super Bowl rings and a glittering stack of 
statistics. He had 142 sacks in his career and all but 
revolutionized his position with his athleticism and mental 
approach. Former Washington Redskins quarterback Joe Theismann 
said, ``If there ever was a Superman in the NFL, I think he wore 
number 56 for the Giants.'' 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
