<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Governors Ponder Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Ten governors swapped veto pens for neon  
crayons Saturday as they followed a 10-year-old's drawing 
directions during an exercise designed to showcase high-achieving 
youngsters at a magnet school. 
</P>
<P>
	The assignment from sixth-grader Janay Anderson was amusing, but  
the governors' goal was serious: boosting student achievement by 
changing how students are taught -- and finding money to pay for it. 
</P>
<P>
	Education is the theme of the four-day meeting of the National  
Governors Association, with 45 chief executives scheduled to attend 
meetings on school accountability, harnessing technology and new 
ways of teaching. 
</P>
<P>
	For a classroom experience, the governors came to Gateway  
Elementary, a math, science and technology magnet school in the 
city's downtown. 
</P>
<P>
	The group did its best to draw the friendly monster, as  
instructed. Each drawing turned out about the same: creatures with 
an L-shaped nose, a square orange head topped by a crown, three 
orange fingers on each hand and purple boots with toes jutting 
outward. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've finally found something I can do well,'' joked GOP Gov.  
William Janklow of South Dakota. 
</P>
<P>
	The school, a product of federal court-ordered desegregation  
funding, cost $25 million to build and millions more to operate 
each year. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a desegregation settlement, the state's forced spending is  
coming to an end. But the school holds such promise as a model for 
the future of learning that the city school board has committed to 
continued funding, said the board president, Marlene Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	She said neither Gateway's cost nor its ambitious programs  
should frighten the governors. The schools offers five computers 
with Internet capability per classroom; a courtyard that is also a 
classroom, complete with a prairie, windmill and weather station; 
and one teacher and a student teacher for every 24 students. 
</P>
<P>
	Gateway is open to any student in St. Louis public schools. They  
are selected by lottery, and there is a 1,000-student waiting list. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, St. Louis school officials said the quality of learning  
at Gateway increasingly is available at other city schools. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is doable in other states. The first thing you have to do  
is make a commitment to make it happen,'' Davis said in an 
interview. 
</P>
<P>
	The governors are exploring creative ways to find money for  
schools. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, Democratic Gov. Thomas Carper of Delaware said his  
state set aside $30 million from a court settlement to wire all 
classrooms for the Internet. In Minnesota, Reform Party Gov. Jesse 
Ventura supported extra state aid for schools that met goals of 
reducing class sizes to 17 students for every teacher. 
</P>
<P>
	Missouri has made technology grants available to all schools,  
and that money usually is matched locally, said Democratic Gov. Mel 
Carnahan. 
</P>
<P>
	Utah's Michael Leavitt, a Republican who is the incoming  
chairman of the governors' group, urged building ``ubiquitous 
capacity'' for students and teachers to reach high-speed Internet 
connections. 
</P>
<P>
	That is just what was displayed at Gateway, where Janay and her  
classmates have an electronic friendship with a two-room elementary 
school in Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is important for students to go beyond classroom walls,''  
said Janay, who told Carper she aims to become a corporate lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	``My guess is you will be -- and I want to buy stock in the  
corporation,'' Carper replied. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
