<DOCNO> APW19990807.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 19:19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> President Lauds Author Willie Morris </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Author Willie Morris was ``the classic  
Southerner'' who helped outward-looking young people recognize they 
could love the South ``and want to change it at the same time,'' 
President Clinton writes in Time magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	Mississippian Morris died Monday of a heart attack at age 64. He  
wrote more than a dozen books during a wide-ranging career as 
journalist, editor and novelist. At 33, he became the youngest 
editor ever of Harper's Magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	In a two-paragraph essay that Time released Saturday, Clinton  
wrote that he met Morris in New York in 1968, the year after he 
took over at Harper's. Clinton, just selected for a Rhodes 
scholarship, had written former Rhodes scholar Morris asking for a 
meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``To my surprise, he agreed to see me. He was wonderfully wry  
and funny -- the classic Southerner,'' Clinton wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know, for most of my generation of Southerners who went  
North, the book that stuck in their minds was (Thomas Wolfe's) `You 
Can't Go Home Again.' Willie's `North Toward Home' was a 
beautifully written evocative portrait of one person's love for the 
South who had profound regret over the racial situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton wrote that Morris' perspective ``helped a lot of people  
like me who wanted to see the world and do well up North but also 
come home and live in the South. He showed us how we could love a 
place and want to change it at the same time. ... He showed us we 
could go home.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
