<DOCNO> APW19990807.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 14:10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Outlaws Align With Speedway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- The fast-growing World of Outlaws  
sprint-car circuit is aligning itself with one of the top promoters 
on NASCAR's Winston Cup circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Speedway Motorsports Inc. is planning to start holding World of  
Outlaws races next year at its Winston Cup properties in Atlanta, 
Charlotte, Dallas and Las Vegas and televise them on The Nashville 
Network, industry sources told The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	A news conference to announce the partnership is scheduled for  
Tuesday at Lowe's Motor Speedway at Charlotte. 
</P>
<P>
	The arrangement calls for Concord-based SMI, which holds nearly  
one-third of the races on NASCAR's top circuit, to build half-mile 
dirt tracks at its Winston Cup properties in Georgia, North 
Carolina and Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's Las Vegas Motor Speedway already has a half-mile  
dirt track on its property for World of Outlaws cars and has 
experienced success with the sprint-car circuit. Las Vegas has two 
weekends of racing each year for the winged, open-wheel cars and 
has sold out the events at its 12,000-seat facility, which sits 
about one-fourth of a mile behind the main speedway where the 
Winston Cup cars run. 
</P>
<P>
	The arrangement would improve the visibility of the World of  
Outlaws series, a circuit that several recent surveys have shown to 
be one of the fastest-growing in racing. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal also would provide another revenue stream for SMI,  
which draws the bulk of its profits from races involving stock 
car's top two circuits, the Winston Cup and Busch Grand National 
series. 
</P>
<P>
	SMI officials hope the World of Outlaws cars will be a more  
steady revenue source than the 3-year-old Indy Racing League, which 
has struggled to draw consistent crowds at company facilities. 
</P>
<P>
	The only SMI track that has been able to annually draw IRL  
crowds in excess of 50,000 is Texas Motor Speedway, where IRL 
ticket sales are tied into those for the track's Winston Cup 
weekends. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta, Charlotte and Las Vegas have had difficulty making  
money on IRL events, and SMI is considering dropping the series at 
Charlotte, where three spectators were killed during the circuit's 
race in May. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
