<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-07 09:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> LT, Dickerson, Newsome Enter Hall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CANTON, Ohio (AP) -- Being humble did not get Lawrence Taylor to  
the Pro Football Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet that's what LT was Saturday, a few hours before his official  
induction. 
</P>
<P>
	``I started out just wanting to play high school ball, then  
succeed in college,'' said the player who redefined the outside 
linebacker position in 13 seasons with the New York Giants. 
</P>
<P>
	``Then I wanted to make it in the pros, make All-Pro and finally  
make it to the Hall of Fame. If nothing else goes right in my life, 
at least that was one thing I did that was complete.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That last reference was to Taylor's well-publicized, off-field  
problems, including drug arrests and suspensions and financial 
woes. But in the past month, as he's prepared for his induction, he 
seems to have tried to come to terms with his troubled past -- 
suggesting, for example, that he's grateful it was he rather than 
his children who had bouts with drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	Inducted with Taylor, who made the Hall on the first ballot  
despite the controversy about his election, were: 
</P>
<P>
	-- Eric Dickerson, the third-leading rusher in NFL history and  
another first-ballot electee; 
</P>
<P>
	-- Tom Mack and Billy Shaw, only the fourth and fifth guards  
elected, and; 
</P>
<P>
	-- Ozzie Newsome, the tight end who played his entire career 60  
miles away with the Cleveland Browns and is now personnel director 
of the Baltimore Ravens. Newsome left Cleveland with the team when 
owner Art Modell moved to Baltimore after the 1995 season. He 
wondered about his welcome here. 
</P>
<P>
	All were a bit tired after two days of breakfasts, lunches,  
dinners, parades and other functions that surround the induction. 
</P>
<P>
	Like Taylor, they all seemed a bit awed.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is the one team you cant be traded from, cut by, or  
retire from,'' Newsome said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, outside of northern Ohio, where Newsome played and Mack  
grew up, most of the attention was on Taylor, who would have been 
an automatic, non-debatable choice if not for his off-field 
headlines. He still made it, but only after prolonged public 
discussion during Super Bowl week, when the vote was taken. 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor said the three people who most influenced his career with  
the Giants from 1981-93 were Bill Parcells, who coached him on 
Super Bowl winners in 1986 and 1990; George Young, the general 
manager then, and Wellington Mara, the owner. 
</P>
<P>
	``He probably cared more about me as a person than he really  
should have,'' Taylor said, referring to Mara, who has helped him 
with his personal problems. 
</P>
<P>
	And speaking about Parcells, now coach of the New York Jets, he  
said: 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like one of those marriages that's been going for 30  
years. You really don't talk much, but you know you love each 
other.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
